<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Arms Agency to Be Absorbed by State Department </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency (ACDA) will go out of business Wednesday
midnight after a 38-year run that included the negotiation of
international agreements aimed at controlling nuclear, biological
and chemical weapons, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The functions of the ACDA will be taken over by the U.S. State
Department.
</P>
<P>
John Holum, who has served as ACDA director since 1993, is due
to become the first undersecretary of state for arms control and
international security affairs, once he is confirmed by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
The agency was created in 1961 as an independent voice within
the government on behalf of arms control.
</P>
<P>
The legislation implementing the merger states that the arms
control office may continue to advocate a point of view which is
at odds with that of the secretary of state, Holum said at a
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"Something unusual is going to happen at midnight tonight, and
that is a federal agency will disappear," Holum said.
</P>
<P>
He said the cost savings of the merger already have been
realized in the form of a 6 percent personnel cutback.
</P>
<P>
As part of the merger process, the U.S. Information Agency also
will be absorbed by the State Department. The merger will take
place in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
