<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: NATO Bombs Cut Lifeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CACAK, Yugoslavia, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Boja Bojic, 52, has
toiled in the Sloboda home appliances plant for three decades. For
him, the factory has been the lifeline of his family.
</P>
<P>
Not any more.
</P>
<P>
Sloboda, or Freedom, the largest employer in the town of
100,000 residents, was struck by over 20 NATO bombs and missiles
in the early hours of Sunday and Tuesday, leaving its 5,000
employees jobless.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not a savage. We work here to earn our bread and make
28-56 dollars a month. Today, we have nothing," Bojic said.
</P>
<P>
Radomir Ljujic, the factory's general manager, told three
busloads of foreign journalists Wednesday that 80 percent of the
sprawling plant had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Workers were clearing the debris and scavenging for what was
left in the ruins 160 kilometers south of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The factory produces ovens, hair dryers and vacuum cleaners
rather than military hardware as the NATO had claimed, Ljujic
said.
</P>
<P>
About 10 people, all of them security guards, were wounded in
the first night, said Ljujic, who was also inside the factory when
it was bombed.
</P>
<P>
At a crater about six meters deep and 10 meters across, one
could still smell dust and gunpowder. The roofs were ripped off
and some galvanized iron sheets landed several hundred meters away
across the road. Some were perching in the trees' branches.
</P>
<P>
One section of the bombed warehouses was cordoned off. The
manager said there were two unexploded missiles there waiting for
sappers to tackle.
</P>
<P>
Asked what made the NATO choose his factory as a target, Ljujic
said he had been looking for answers for days.
</P>
<P>
The factory, which cooperated with Siemens and Bosch of Germany
and Iglis of Italy a few years ago, was still producing the
appliances using the license of Siemens.
</P>
<P>
In the clearance outside the warehouses and work shops were
piles of Biljana hair dryers, a Sloboda electric stove with a hole
in the cover and vacuum cleaners of Sloboda 3000 and Sloboda 700
models.
</P>
<P>
With nowhere to work, Bojic was wondering how to support his
wife and children.
</P>
<P>
"We'd like to see (U.S. President) Bill Clinton's daughter to
be with our children here," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This can only be done by those who has no senses, has not
hearts," Bojic said, sorting through the broken parts in the work
shop where engines for vacuum cleaners were assembled.
</P>
<P>
"Can vacuum cleaners kill," asked Miloze Basnnokovic, a power
engineer.
</P>
<P>
Ljujic, the manager, said his factory, which celebrated its
50th anniversary last year, lost 300 million dollars as a result
of the NATO bombings.
</P>
<P>
Facing the foreign reporters, many from countries that
participated in the NATO air raids, Ljujic said: "Tell those who
decided to bomb us that the factory has not been totally
destroyed."
</P>
<P>
Amid the mounting rage against NATO air raids, which entered
its eighth day Wednesday, none of the reporters from the western
media had their agencies' logos on their equipment.
</P>
<P>
One worker, a wooden club in hand, demanded: "Who's American?
Who's British?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
