<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Denounces Serb Actions in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia denounced Wednesday
the Serb actions in Kosovo, saying they led to "the killing and
displacing of hundreds of thousands of Muslim Kosovars."
</P>
<P>
A Saudi official lashed out at "the policy of collective
punishment and ethnic cleansing" pursued by the Yugoslav
government against the Muslim people of Kosovo, the Saudi News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, condemned
what he called "intransigence" of the Yugoslav government in
rejecting the international efforts aimed at solving the Kosovo
crisis peacefully and notably in the contact group talks in France.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Serb-led government and independence-seeking
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo intensified early last year.
</P>
<P>
The contact group, consisting of Russia, the U.S., France,
Britain, Germany and Italy, hammered out a ceasefire proposal,
which was rejected by Yugoslav government and accepted by ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) has launched air
strikes against Serb targets since last Wednesday after it claimed
the diplomatic efforts were exhausted.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi official did not comment on the NATO air strikes. But
he said Saudi Arabia supports the Kosovars that are suffering the
"cruelest kind of oppression and homelessness at the hands of the
aggressive Serbs," highlighting the necessity of putting an end to
these actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
