<HEADLINE> IGC's Outlook For World Wheat Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- On the basis of information
currently available, world wheat production is forecast at 569
million tons, compared with 583 million tons in 1998, said a
report by the International Grains Council (IGC).
</P>
<P>
In its latest issue of Grain Market Report, the IGC said: "Wet
weather and a higher set-aside rate curtailed sowings in the EC,
and the winter wheat area in the U.S. is the lowest since 1972."
</P>
<P>
However, "Some return from oilseeds to wheat could boost the
outturn in Canada, and India could see a near record harvest," it
added.
</P>
<P>
World wheat consumption is forecast at a record 592 million
tons, with food use at 437 million and world wheat trade is
forecast to rise by 6 million to 99 million tons, the IGC said.
</P>
<P>
Taking account of initial projections for world supply and
demand, world wheat stocks are forecast to fall by 24 million to
105 million tons, which would be the lowest since 1980, according
to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
