<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ties With China Important: Clinton's Security Advisor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. relationship with
China is so important that its nature will have a profound effect
on America's future interests, not only in Asia, but globally, a
prominent Security Advisor to U.S. President Bill Clinton said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech prior to the expected upcoming visit of
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji, Kenneth Lieberthal, senior director of
the U.S. National Security Council, said that if China were to be
at loggerheads in a serious fashion with the U.S., that would
vastly complicate the world.
</P>
<P>
"We would run into increased problems in everything from
proliferation to international economics, to stability in
Northeast Asia," he said, adding that an antagonist relationship
between the U.S. and China is neither in the interest of the U.S.,
nor China and others in Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said U.S. diplomacy in the U.S. relationship with China,
which is called comprehensive engagement, "means that we seek to
deal with China, to increase mutual understanding, to develop
cooperation where our interests permit this, and to provide frank
advice where we think the other side in in error."
</P>
<P>
On China's accession to international institutions such as the
World Trade Organization (WTO), he said any such organization
without China falls at least 22 percent short of being global in
scope.
</P>
<P>
"If you aspire to a post-Cold War world that is governed in the
main by agreement on international norms, and by institutions to
express those norms and provide a regulatory framework," he said,
"you really need to work to get China constructively into those
institutions. "
</P>
<P>
Admitting that "non-trivial issues" remain on the table, he
said that to bring China into the WTO would make the WTO virtually
global in scope and would subject China to the international rules
of the game in its trade regime.
</P>
<P>
He said a WTO agreement is a "win-win," good not only for U.S.
business and interests, but also for China and Chinese interests.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about China's faith in implementing the
WTO agreement, Kenneth, a China expert who has been watching China
for 30 years, said it depends on China's political will and the
WTO's institutional capacity. "I think the Chinese would enter
this regime in good faith," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If you look at China's participation in multilateral
organizations, almost without exception, China is not an outlier,"
he said. "It is not the one everyone points to as the one that's
impossible to deal with."
</P>
<P>
He also said China has made "tremendous progress" in human
rights, effective rule based on law, effective protection of
property rights, etc. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
