<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat to Discuss Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak is
to hold talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on the latest
developments in the Mideast peace process, Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, a frequent visitor to Egypt, is due to arrive in Cairo
on Thursday for a brief visit, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the two leaders will dwell on the outcome of
Arafat's recent visits to a number of European countries and the
United States, he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has announced that he would declare an independent
Palestinian state on May 4 when the five-year interim self-rule
period under the Oslo Accord signed with Israel in 1993 expires.
</P>
<P>
Israel is opposed to the Palestinian plan, threatening to take
tough actions against the possible step, including annexation of
the parts of the West Bank under its control.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has been under mounting pressure from the West and the
Arab countries to postpone the declaration of statehood. It is
feared a unilateral declaration of Palestinian statehood would
further stalk the deadlocked Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
During his recent European and U.S. visit, Arafat has tried to
win the support from the world community for the Palestinian plan
and recognition for the future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The talks also follow a statement of the European Union (EU) on
recognizing the Palestinian people's right to establish their own
independent state, Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The EU issued last Thursday a statement that the Palestinians
have "unqualified right to self-determination, including the
option of a state."
</P>
<P>
Moussa described EU's stance as "important," saying it
formulates the world public opinion.
</P>
<P>
Any coming Israeli government will face such a stance, which
means that the issue of the Palestinian statehood does not and
should not be subject to Israeli veto, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Israel is scheduled to hold general elections on May 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
