<HEADLINE> Study Finds Much of Rainwater in Europe Unfit to Drink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Much of the rain falling in Europe
contains such high levels of dissolved pesticides that it would be
unfit to be used as drinking water, Swiss researchers said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Swiss Federal Institute for Environmental
Science and Technology have found that rainwater in Europe is full
of toxic chemicals used in crop sprays, which appear to have
evaporated from fields and become part of the clouds.
</P>
<P>
Both the European Union and Switzerland have set a limit of 100
nanograms for any particular pesticide in a liter of drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
But scientists found that European rainwater can contain much
more than that, especially in the first minutes of a heavy storm.
</P>
<P>
"Drinking water standards are regularly exceeded in rain,"
Stephan Muller, one of the researchers, told the New Scientist
magazine.
</P>
<P>
Muller and his colleague found in a study that one sample of
rainwater contained almost 4,000 nanograms per liter of
2-4-dinitrophenol, a widely used pesticide.
</P>
<P>
Some of their previous research also showed that in rain
samples taken from 41 storms, nine contained more than 100
nanograms of atrazine per liter, one of them around 900 nanograms.
</P>
<P>
Until now, scientists had assumed that the pesticides only
infiltrated groundwater directly from fields.
</P>
<P>
However, Muller and his colleagues found that the highest
concentrations of pesticides turned up in the first rain after a
long dry spell, particularly when local fields had recently been
sprayed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
