<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Environmental experts around the world will convene on
April 20-21 in Dubai to discuss ways of maritime environment
protection in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the International Research Institute (IIR), the
conference will focus on exploring systems and ways of protecting
the environment of the coastal areas in the region.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The free zone authority in Saadiyat, Abu Dhabi
Emirate, has started to handle license applications of companies
showing interests in the zone.
</P>
<P>
The authority plans to attract some 170 billion U.S. dollars to
the Emirate in the coming 25 years, the Arabic daily Al Hayat
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Ali Al Husseini, the general manager of the authority,
said "hand-written replies will shortly be issued to the companies
that have expressed desire to participate in Saadiyat project."
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Beirut Harbor Management and Investment Authority
has issued a decree abolishing charge of 15 dollars per tourist.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily Alam Al Yom reported Wednesday the decision
was made after maritime travel companies halted trips to Beirut
port as of last December when fees were first levied on tourists.
</P>
<P>
A maritime travel agency has announced a German tourist ship
"Berlini" arrived at Beirut port last Saturday with 400 tourists
and 24 crewmen.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has so far exported to Iraq 82 million dollars
worth of goods in the fifth phase of the oil-for-food deal between
the U.N. and Iraq, which runs from December to June.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette reported Wednesday Egypt's exports
included 61.4 million dollars of foodstuffs and detergents, 12
million dollars of medicines and 500,000 dollars of school
supplies.
</P>
<P>
The English-language newspaper quoted a report prepared by
Egypt's trade office as saying Egypt's exports are expected
to reach 120 million dollars by the end of the phase.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon is to receive 100 million dollars from the
World Bank to finance education projects, the Daily Star reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Mohammed Youssef Beydou made the
announcement after a meeting with a delegation of the bank
Tuesday, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will provide another 50 million dollars
for the projects, which are expected to begin next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
