<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Reportedly not to Observe Arms Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Russian Ambassador to Cyprus
Georgi Mouradov Wednesday said Russia will no more observe the
U.N. arms embargo on Yugoslavia since it has already been violated
the NATO, Cyprus News Agency reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with Cyprus House (parliament) Speaker
Spyros Kyprianou, he said the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) has violated the relevant U.N. resolution about arms
embargo on Yugoslavia, adding arms provisions are already finding
their way into Kosovo openly by NATO forces to Kosovo army.
</P>
<P>
"We have certain indications that a ground offensive is being
prepared," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mouradov expressed fears that the NATO is trying to apply a new
world order, which entails recognition of the right of powerful
nations to set up a separate state through military intervention
and occupation of part of a smaller state.
</P>
<P>
Mouradov said some American politicians are talking about
Kosovo's secession, which effectively means giving the right to
powerful states to create a separate state by force.
</P>
<P>
"This is terrible because it has ramifications for many other
countries," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Mouradov conveyed to Kyprianou a statement by Russian State
Duma on the Yugoslav crisis, which describes the NATO's air
strikes as "a serious threat to the security of the Russian
Federation" and calls for "an immediate cessation of military
attacks."
</P>
<P>
The statement recommends, among other things, to Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and the government to "take measures on
increasing the readiness of the military forces of the Russian
Federation" and calls for an extraordinary session of the
U.N. General Assembly to discuss the aggression against a
U.N. member. 
</P>
</TEXT>
