<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economy Grows by 3.9 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The real gross domestic
product (GDP) of the United States surged at a seasonally adjusted
6 percent annual rate during the fourth quarter of last year,
bringing the growth for the whole year to a robust 3.9 percent,
the Commerce Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The revised GDP estimate for the last three months of 1998 was
down slightly from the department's preliminary estimate of 6.1
percent released last month, and the growth estimate for the year
was left unchanged. The real GDP stood at 7,551.9 billion U.S.
dollars last year, 282.1 billion dollars more than that in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
However, the department's first estimate of after-tax corporate
profits for the fourth quarter showed a drop at a 1 percent rate,
marking the third quarterly decline of the year.
</P>
<P>
And for all of 1998, profits fell 2.2 percent, the first drop
since 1989, when profits declined 4.8 percent in a precursor to
the 1990-91 recession.
</P>
<P>
Profits are being pinched by the combination of increasing
labor costs and the inability of manufacturing firms to raise
prices in the face of stiff price competition from imports
produced in countries with devalued currencies.
</P>
<P>
A price index tied to the GDP rose just 1 percent in 1998.
There hasn't been a rate that low since 1959, also 1 percent, and
there hasn't been one lower since 1950.
</P>
<P>
Labor costs are increasing because the long expansion, which
began its ninth year in March, reduced the unemployment rate to a
29-year low last year.
</P>
<P>
Plentiful jobs and surging stock prices have been the principal
fuel of the growth in consumer spending, which represents about
two-thirds of economic activity. It rose at a 5 percent seasonally
adjusted annual rate in the fourth quarter and 4.9 percent for all
of 1998, the most in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
In addition to wages, consumers spent some of their stock gains
and tapped their home equity in a wave of refinancing last year
after mortgage rates fell to three-decade lows.
</P>
<P>
Those, in turn, produced a big drop in the nation's savings
rate -- savings as a percentage of after-tax income -- from 2.1
percent in 1997 to just 0.5 percent in 1998, the lowest since
1933. The rate was zero during the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
Also contributing to economic growth were business investment
in computers and other new equipment, up 16.5 percent last year,
and housing construction, up 10.4 percent, the most since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Overseas economic turmoil, however, held U.S. exports to only a
1.5 percent increase, the weakest in 15 years, while imports shot
up 10.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
