<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Fails to Agree on New Chief Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Members of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) failed again to decide who will lead the
organization into the new century after a last-minute meeting here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Trade officials said that delegations of the WTO's 134 members
faced difficulties in choosing a new director-general by
consensus.
</P>
<P>
"It is with deep regret that I have to report to you that the
difficulties faced by both candidates are so serious that neither
of them can enjoy consensus from the membership to enable them to
be elected as the next director-general," said Ambassador Ali
Mchumo of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Mchumo, elected on February 16 as chairman of the WTO's
governing body General Council, took full charge of the
consultations among WTO members in the selection process from his
predecessor, Ambassador John Weekes of Canada.
</P>
<P>
"This is most unfortunate and disappointing," said Mchumo. "We
had all wanted to conclude this process by today at the latest in
order for us to devote our attention to more substantive issues in
the WTO. We all have to prepare for the Seattle Ministerial, for
instance."
</P>
<P>
Missing the end-March deadline, the delegations will meet next
week in Geneva following the Easter holiday.
</P>
<P>
Mchumo expressed the hope that the WTO members would elect the
new director-general at the regular General Council meeting set
for April 14.
</P>
<P>
Originally, there were four candidates to run for the WTO
position. Since Hassan Abuyoub of Morocco quit and Roy MacLaren of
Canada suspended the contest after failing to gather sufficient
backing, Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand and Michael Moore of
New Zealand have been the only two candidates eligible in the
contest.
</P>
<P>
Supachai has been in the lead since the WTO began to choose its
new director-general in the fourth quarter of 1998, but Moore is
believed to have support from the United States and majority
support from Latin America and much of the sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
The WTO members have missed several deadlines before to agree
on their new leader.
</P>
<P>
The incumbent WTO director-general, Renato Ruggiero, will leave
his post on April 30 at the end of a four-year term in office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0025 </DOCNO>
