<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Explains Why Drinking Green Tea Prevents Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A chemical found in green tea
which inhibits the growth of new blood vessels in animals may
explain why drinking green tea prevents cancer, researchers said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Drinking tea, especially green tea, is associated with a lower
incidence of cancer in humans and has been shown to suppress the
growth of several types of tumor in animals, but how and why tea
has such an effect is less clear.
</P>
<P>
Now two China-born Swedish scientists have found for the first
time that a substance in green tea called
epigallocatechin-3-gallate or EGCG, significantly prevents
angiogenesis, a process of blood-vessel growth, in mice.
</P>
<P>
This may explain the cancer inhibition mechanism of green tea
as angiogenesis is particularly important for tumor growth and
spread, Yihai Cao, one of the researchers, told Xinhua Wednesday
in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
Cao, an associate professor at the Karolinska Institute,
Stockholm, Sweden, said that their study, to be published in the 1
April issue of the science journal Nature, could also help expand
the applications of green tea in medical treatments.
</P>
<P>
The result indicates that drinking tea may be beneficial for
the prevention and treatment of angiogenesis-dependent diseases,
including blindness caused by diabetes, Cao said.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that according to their new findings,
pregnant women may better avoid tea as they need promotion rather
than prevention of blood vessel growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Considers to Deregister 300 Publications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is considering to
deregister more than 300 publications which have failed to print
for a long time.
</P>
<P>
The Director of Tanzania Information Services, Kassim Mpenda,
told Xinhua here Wednesday that the government has issued a 90-day
notice, effective from March 16, to 315 publications asking them
to submit copies of their publications on every production day.
</P>
<P>
If they cannot show their copies and fail to give good reasons
for it, their registration certificates will be scrapped off,
Mpenda said.
</P>
<P>
"We want you to publish. We don't want you to keep your
registration certificate in your pocket," he said.
</P>
<P>
Another government information officer said: "There is a law in
our country -- once a newspaper is registered, it should come out
as regularly as it is asked to publish."
</P>
<P>
Under the Newspaper Act of 1976, publishers are supposed to
submit copies of every issue to the Registrar of Newspapers at
their own expenses so that the government can make sure that they
are operational.
</P>
<P>
A number of Tanzanian publications have failed to come out with
even one copy after they got registered, forcing the government to
take measures against them, Mpenda said.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the government may issue notices next month to
another 200 publications which have not come out regularly as
expected.
</P>
<P>
Some papers, such as Mwananchi, Ngurumo, Motomoto, Fahari,
Wakati ni Huu and Mizani were publishing for a period of time but
later were out of circulation.
</P>
<P>
Other publication, like Daily Times, Bayana, Jambo and Harakati
and the Tanzania Law Magazine, have not been published since they
were registered, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mpenda also said by deregistering the publications, their names
can be used by others who wish to launch a new paper or magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
