<HEADLINE> Iranian President Expresses Concern Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami on Wednesday expressed deep concern over the worsening
situation in Kosovo following airstrikes launched by the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In a message to heads of Islamic countries, Khatami warned
against continuation of the killing, displacement of innocent
civilians and possible expansion of the crisis to other parts of
the Balkans, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The attacks by the NATO on Yugoslavia will further complicate
the crisis, said Khatami, who is also current chairman of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
He said the heads of state of the OIC member countries
burden the responsibility of preventing repetition of the bitter
experiences of the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
Khatami also instructed his foreign minister Kamal Kharrazi to
contact his counterparts in the OIC contact group to prepare the
preliminaries for a new move, along with other international
institutions, in a bid to find a principled solution to the crisis
and help restore a lasting peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
After the NATO started military strikes on Yugoslavia last
Wednesday, Iran expressed grave concern over the situation in the
Balkan region and called for a peaceful solution to the crisis
through political efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
