<HEADLINE> Mubarak Meets with U.S. Congress Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and a U.S. Congress delegation on Wednesday discussed U.S. aid to
Egypt and the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and the delegation led by Benjamin Gilman, chairman of
the U.S. House International Relations Committee, discussed
economic and cultural ties, Mubarak's top advisor Osman el-Baz
told reporters after the meeting in the Sinai resort of Sharm
El-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also dealt with the issue of U.S. military aid to
Egypt, el-Baz was quoted by Egypt's Middle East News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Egypt receives 1.2 billion U.S. dollars annually from the
United States in military aid.
</P>
<P>
El-Baz said the two sides also discussed ways of reviving the
Arab-Israeli peace talks after the May 17 Israeli elections.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks came to a halt in December when
Israel shelved the Wye peace agreement signed last October in
Washington after it carried out the first of a three-phase
withdrawal from another 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel-Syria and Israel-Lebanon negotiations broke down in
early 1996 due to disputes over the future of the Golan Heights
captured by Israel in the 1967 Mideast War from Syria.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to realize peace with Israel, has
been an active mediator in the Middle East peace process.
U.S. officials often consult with Mubarak on issues related to the
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
