<HEADLINE> U.S. Army to Train Zimbabweans on Removing Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A team of United States army
officers arrived in Harare Wednesday to train the Zimbabweans to
remove land mines planted along Zimbabwe's borders during the
country's liberation struggle in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The team led by General Robert Coffey brought demining
expertise and 756, 000 U.S. dollars to purchase equipment which
will be donated to the Zimbabwean army, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Coffey said that Zimbabwe was doing an important job in
clearing areas infested with land mines for the sake of innocent
people's life.
</P>
<P>
He said that the demining exercise would go a long way in
bringing relief to people who lived in those areas infested with
land mines.
</P>
<P>
A lot of people in developing countries continued to be maimed
or killed by land mines because they had little knowledge of the
deadly weapons, said the U.S. general.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has mine fields on its peripheral districts which
cover an area of 678 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The land mines were planted during the war of liberation
struggle between 1976 and 1979. 
</P>
