<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Drop Sharply in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- New orders to the U.S.
factories fell sharply in February as demand for costly
transportation goods like new commercial aircraft contracted
significantly, the Commerce Department said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Total factory orders were down 2.5 percent to 340.5 billion
U.S. dollars, the biggest monthly falloff since a 2.6 percent
plunge in April 1995, following a revised 1.5 percent January
increase.
</P>
<P>
Orders for transportation equipment dropped 14.4 percent to
44.9 billion dollars, with aircraft orders down 30.6 percent.
Transportation orders increased by 13.5 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
However, economists said the manufacturing sector should
continue to be supported by healthy domestic demand. Manufacturing
has been gradually recovering after lagging other key sectors like
homebuilding throughout much of the long-running expansion.
</P>
<P>
A separate report, from Chicago purchasing agents, showed a
sharp spike upward in March manufacturing activity in the Midwest.
Its regional index climbed to 57.0 from 52.9 in February and
included increases in new orders, production and employment in
March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
