<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: One Falls Down, Thousands Stand Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KRAGUJEVAC, Yugoslavia, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-eight years
ago, a primary school teacher known as Miloje Pavlovic chose to
die with his pupils by pointing toward his chest as the target for
Nazi gunshots.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-eight years after, upwards of 10,000 people chose to be
bombed by pasting bull's eye onto their chest, back and forehead
as the target for NATO cruise missiles and bombs.
</P>
<P>
Both stories took place at Kragujevac in central Serbia, where
people coming from far and wide on Wednesday to the memorial
service of the 7,000 innocent people who were killed by the Nazis
on October 21, 1941.
</P>
<P>
The primary school teacher was told to stand away from his
pupils to shun death but he chose otherwise while the people at
Kragujevac chose not to succumb to the pressure of the western
society.
</P>
<P>
They chose, rather, to be bombed.
</P>
<P>
Not far from the monument erected to commemorate the 7,000
people killed by Nazi during World War II, there were three bomb
craters left by the first round of NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
Though the bombs were close enough to civilian housing to have
done severe damage, local people still thought that NATO was off
target and offered to help train NATO cruise missiles and bombs by
using black-and-white and red-and-white target papers.
</P>
<P>
Even the handicapped in wheelchairs and toddlers in baby prams
had target papers pasted to their arm-rests and sun-shades.
</P>
<P>
Jaswin Varkovic, a 19-year-old choir soprano, was so moved by
the brave gathering that she sang with her troupe mates the
national anthem, orthodoxic requiem and Serbian folksong, all with
tears in her eyes.
</P>
<P>
The first-year college student of English language said that
she was scared the first night NATO bombs fell upon her hometown
but she no longer felt scared as the bombs continued to fall and
especially after she saw so many brave people gathered around the
monument to defy western pressure and aerial invasion.
</P>
<P>
She said that her choir's message was peace to the world
whereas NATO's message were missiles and bombs to her nation.
</P>
<P>
As yellow narcissus wavering and candle flames dancing in the
breeze, hundreds of pigeons flew up with the song "Rise Serbia"
that was composed during the first World War to urge the people of
the country to resist the invasion of others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
