<HEADLINE> Mozambique, Mauritius Ink Pact for Mutual Visa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Mozambique and
Mauritius signed an agreement in Maputo, Mozambican capital,
Wednesday for mutual exemption of visa for the convenience of
personnel movement from both countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the Mozambican News Agency, Mozambican Foreign
Minister Leonardo Simao and Mauritian Minister of Economic
Development Affairs Rudheersing Bheenick signed the agreement on
behalf of their governments.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, Simao said that the pact was aimed
at promoting trade and exchange of both personnel and materials
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
With the agreement, "the citizens from both countries can enter
the other country and stay there for one month without visa,"
Simao noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that the agreement will be effective as soon as the
two governments exchange the approved document.
</P>
<P>
The pact has been designed to expire after a term of five
years. But its term will automatically extend for another five
years unless one side declares to give it up 60 days before its
expiration date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
