<HEADLINE> S.African President Encourages N. Ireland Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela Wednesday urged parties in the faltering Northern
Ireland peace talks to find common ground, South African Press
Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the plea as the anniversary of last year's Good Friday
accord approaches.
</P>
<P>
Mandela issued a formal message of support following phone
calls he made earlier this week to leaders involved in the
negotiations, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said Wednesday that South Africa's own experience in
overcoming the divisions of centuries showed that even the deepest
and most difficult problems could be resolved through talks and
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
"The Good Friday agreement has our full support, because we
believe that its final implementation will assure Northern Ireland
of the better future it deserves, a future of lasting peace based
on democracy and respect for human rights," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, negotiated last year, aims to set up a new
Protestant- Catholic government, which is to receive powers
gradually from the British government and pursue joint
police-making with the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
But the talks have stalled over the insistence of the largest
Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, that the Irish Republican
Army must start to disarm before its political wing, Sinn Fein,
can receive two posts in the government.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's spokesman, Parks Mankahlana, confirmed Wednesday that
Mandela had phoned Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams, Ulster Unionists
head David Trimble, who was elected to lead the new government,
and Seamus Mallon, the moderate Catholic elected as his
deputy-to-be. 
</P>
</TEXT>
