<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Prices Breakthrough above 15 Dollars Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- World oil prices passed a key
milestone on Wednesday, hitting a new 10-month high over 15 U.S.
dollars, on the joint forces of gasoline demand in the United
States and continued trader faith in producer output cuts.
</P>
<P>
International benchmark North Sea Brent broke through the 15
dollars a barrel level for the first time since May 1998, to trade
up to 15.30 dollars in afternoon business in London before closing
at 15.22 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brent has gained around 4 dollars this month on major oil
producers' decision to reduce output and knock down what has been
a chronic overhang in global oil inventories.
</P>
<P>
The North Sea benchmark averaged a mere 13.34 dollars a barrel
in 1998 and has managed an average of just 11.50 dollars so far
this year.
</P>
<P>
Markets took further heart on Wednesday from the perception of
strained gasoline supplies on the West Coast of the United States,
where a series of refinery disruptions have hindered production
just as the U.S. driving season begins, according to a Reuters oil
analyst.
</P>
<P>
Two major explosions at West Coast refineries helped cut
gasoline inventories there by nearly 600,000 barrels last week,
with national stockpiles down some 5.4 million barrels, according
to statistics from the American Petroleum Institute (API).
</P>
<P>
Data from the U.S. Department of Energy confirmed the stock
draw, calculating a weekly decline in gasoline inventories of 5.3
million barrels.
</P>
<P>
A rise in U.S. inventories of crude oil worked to counter the
positive sentiment, but analysts expressed optimism about the
market's long-term prospects, saying funds and trade buyers
appeared to be locking into more longer term positions in
anticipation of further price gains, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
"The market (Brent) is incredibly constructive at the moment;
it's overbought but it's not losing momentum; there's just no
stopping it," Independent Consultant Elli Gifford was quoted
saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
