<HEADLINE> Blair, Ahern Fly Back to N.Ireland to Save Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and his Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern went back to Northern
Ireland Wednesday evening to rescue the province's deadlocked
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Blair and Ahern left the talks earlier in the day to attend to
government matters in their capitals and promised to come back
when necessary.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders have brokered three days of talks to try to break
a stalemate over decommissioning that has blocked formation of a
coalition cabinet that will inherit some home-rule powers from
London -- a key provision of the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
John Hume, a moderate Roman Catholic architect of the peace
process, said he was hopeful some compromise would be reached in
Wednesday night's talks.
</P>
<P>
Irish Republican Army (IRA)'s refusal to disarm itself has
triggered a row between Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble and
the IRA's political wing Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
Trimble has refused to admit Sinn Fein to the cabinet until the
IRA gives up the weapons it used to wage a 30-year campaign
against British rule.
</P>
<P>
The British government has set the week running up to this Good
Friday, April 2, as a final deadline for the implementation of the
peace accord. 
</P>
