<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Parliament Passes Refugee Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SOFIA, April 1 (Xinhua) - With no debates, and almost
unanimously, the Bulgarian Parliament passed a refugee bill on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Moving the bill to the plenary chamber was not prompted only
by the Kosovo crisis, said Ivan Soungarski, chief of the
parliamentary human rights committee. He said that work on the
bill started a long time ago and its passage is part of Bulgaria's
steps to integrate into European structures.
</P>
<P>
The bill was put on Parliament's agenda by proposal of the
opposition Socialist party early last month.
</P>
<P>
A refugee in Bulgaria can be any foreigner who has reasons to
fear persecution because of his race, religion, political
affiliations or for belonging to a certain public group.
</P>
<P>
A refugee can also be a foreigner who is out of the country in
which he is a citizen, or if he does not have citizenship but is
out of the country of his permanent residence, or he refuses to
accept its protection and refuses to return to it for fear of
persecution. A refugee's spouse and children can also get refugee
status.
</P>
<P>
Refugee status will not be granted to persons who are
suspected of having been involved in war crimes, or a crime
against peace and humanity. The restriction applies to foreigners
who are suspected perpetrators of a grave crime of nonpolitical
character outside Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
The competent authorities may refuse to grant such status to
persons who are citizens of, or live permanently in a country that
is considered to be safe. Foreigners who have entered Bulgaria to
seek refugee status may not be returned to the country where they
feel threatened.
</P>
<P>
Refugees and persons applying for refugee status have civil,
administrative and criminal liability to the regulations that
apply to Bulgarian citizens.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria will provide humanitarian protection to refugees up
to one year and may be extended to another year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
