<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania, Greece Against Territorial Revision in Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Romania's Defense Minister
Victor Babiuc and his visiting Greek counterpart Apostolos
Tsohatzopoulos expressed objections to any territorial revisions
in the Balkan region, stressing that the Kosovo issue should be
resolved through political means.
</P>
<P>
 Following their talks, the two ministers told a joint news
conference on Thursday that Kosovo would enjoy high autonomous
rights on the condition that the territorial integrity of both
Yugoslavia and the Serbian Republic be observed.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos, who arrived here on Thursday for a two-day
official visit, pointed out that the worsening situation in
Yugoslavia will affect the stability and security of the whole
Balkan region, and this should be taken into account at the coming
NATO summit in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Greece also suggested a discussion regarding NATO's expansion
to southeastern Europe by inviting Romania, Bulgaria and Slovenia
to join the military organization, since the three countries are
in a region that has suffered directly the consequences of the
current crisis in Yugoslavia, Tsohatzopoulos said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
