<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai's Sabotage Contributes to Tibet's Backwardness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of southwest
China's Tibet Autonomous Region said here today that "the
disturbance and sabotage of the Dalai Lama clique constitutes one
of the major factors behind the backwardness of Tibet."
</P>
<P>
Basang, deputy secretary of the Tibet Autonomous Regional
Committee of the Chinese Communist Party, made the remark this
afternoon while meeting with visiting member of the United States
House of Representatives Matt Salmon.
</P>
<P>
Basang briefed the visitors on the history of Tibet, saying
that "Tibet has always been an inalienable part of China."
</P>
<P>
She noted that "the feudal serfdom system was practiced in
Tibet until 1959 when democratic reform was introduced into the
region."
</P>
<P>
Some 95 percent of the Tibetan population were serfs without
their own land, pastures, or property, and five percent of the
serfs were slaves who could be exchanged as gifts among serf-
owners, according to Basang.
</P>
<P>
"However, the Dalai Lama regards the system as a sacred,
brilliant, and unchangeable system, and organized an armed
rebellion in 1959 to prevent the introduction of democratic reform
into Tibet. Dalai fled abroad with a small handful of upper-class
splittists when the rebellion failed," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that the attitude of the Chinese government toward the
Dalai Lama is consistent and explicit, "the Dalai Lama can return
to China during his lifetime as long as he completely abandons his
splitting activities, recognizes publicly that Tibet is a part of
China, Taiwan is a province of China, and the fact that the
government of the People's Republic of China is the sole
legitimate government of China."
</P>
<P>
Basang also discussed Tibet's development in the fields of
economy, culture, education, and religious protection.
</P>
<P>
Matt Salmon and two others arrived in Tibet on March 31 at the
invitation of the Chinese People's Institute of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The three visited the Potala Palace, the Jokhang Temple, and
other scenic spots during their stay; the group is scheduled to
leave Tibet for the U.S. tomorrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
