<HEADLINE> Singapore Announces Change of Navy Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the Republic of
Singapore Navy Richard Lim Cherng Yih will be replaced by his
deputy Lui Tuck Yew in July.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Ministry of Defense (MODEF) said in a press release
Thursday that the president has accepted the advice of the prime
minister that Rear Admiral Richard Lim Cherng Yih will relinquish
his appointment as the chief of navy on July 1 and Rear Admiral
Lui Tuck, currently deputy chief of navy, will take over from July
1.
</P>
<P>
The MODEF noted that the prime minister made this
recommendation to the president following consultation with the
Armed Forces Council.
</P>
<P>
The MODEF said that the change is part of the continuing
process of leadership renewal with a view to release talented
officers of Singapore Armed Forces to service in other positions
in the public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
Lim will be attending a Masters Program in September after
relinquishing his appointment, MODEF added. 
</P>
