<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Statistics released by the Central Bank of Lebanon shows
the total bank loans to the country's private sector by the
end of February reached 12.50 billion U.S. dollars, 18.66 percent
higher than 10.40 billion dollars in the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's Alam Al Yom, a daily based in Egypt, also said the
loans constitute 40.60 percent of the total bank deposits of 30.78
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
JEDDA -- SEPCO, a Saudi Arabian company for environmental
projects, is planning to open its first center for treatment
of medical waste in the kingdom next month.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's Al Hayat daily, based in London, quoted the
company's general manager Abdulla Sa'im Al Dahr as saying the
center is located in Jedda and equipped with three microwave sets,
two of which are stationary and the third mobile. The center will
follow a new method which will leave behind no gas waste.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Soliman Metwalli, the Egyptian Minister of Transport
and Communications, announced the establishment of a new telephone
exchange in Cairo with a capacity of 120,000 lines in April and a
number of wireless and control stations, Wednesday's Arab Ahram
Cairo daily reported.
</P>
<P>
He added the Egyptian telecommunications company has embarked
on the extension of the intelligent network to provide vocal post
box service to its subscribers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
