<HEADLINE> Five U.S. B-1 Bombers Arrive at British Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua)-- Five B-1 bombers from the United
States on Thursday arrived in a British airforce base.
</P>
<P>
The bombers, which would fly missions of airstrikes on
Yugoslavia, came from their Ellsworth airforce base in South
Dakota of the U.S. and landed at the Royal Air Force base in
Fairford in Gloucestershire in western England, a BBC report said.
</P>
<P>
The B-1 bombers each has a crew of four and can carry 20 cruise
missiles, the report said.
</P>
<P>
With a sophisticated defense system to detect hostile jets and
can fly 7,500 miles without refueling, the plane can fly at any
time of the day and in all weather, BBC said.
</P>
<P>
The five new arrivals would combine with the 13 U.S. B-52s,
which had already been based in Britain, to bomb the Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
NATO said on Wednesday that it would intensify and widen its
campaign on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
