<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Govt: Kaunda's Citizenship Deprived by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government has said that
depriving former President Kenneth Kaunda's Zambian nationality
is an independent decision of the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Thursday quoted chief government spokesman
Newstead Zimba as saying that it is not the government that passed
the ruling but the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
He said that justice Chalendo Sakala acted independently and
professionally.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will need time to study the judgement
before any more remarks.
</P>
<P>
An official from Kaunda's United National Independence Party
(UNIP) dismissed the judgement as unfair.
</P>
<P>
UNIP's Ndola District chairperson for women's affairs, Evelyn
Chikonde, called on the British government to intervene, saying if
Kaunda is stateless then everyone else in Zambia is a foreigner.
</P>
<P>
She said despite the ruling Kaunda will remain UNIP leader and
continue to enjoy the sport of the party.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Democratic Party Secretary-General Dante Saunders said
the judgement is a great setback for democratic progress in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia quoted UNIP Secretary for Information Publicity
Bwendo Mulengela as saying that the decision is retrogressive.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda's lawyers have appealed to the Supreme Court against
the judgement.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was declared stateless Wednesday by the Ndola High Court
because his parents were Malawians.
</P>
<P>
Judge Chalendo Sakala ordered the citizenship Board of Zambia
to quash the Zambian nationality of Kaunda, who ruled the country
since its independence from 1964 to 1991, when he was defeated by
current President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda were barred from running for president in the elections
held in 1996, when a constitutional amendment was adopted under
which foreign nationals and those with foreign parentage are
prohibited from contesting.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda has vowed to contest the post in the next elections in
2001.  
</P>
</TEXT>
