<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ambitious Thorpe Eyes New World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Ian Thorpe, who smashed a nine-
year-old world record in the men's 200 meters freestyle Thursday
night at the world short-course swimming championships, said that
he would not let the triumph stand in his way.
</P>
<P>
The Australian, 16, finished the distance at 1:43:28, 0.36
better of the old world mark set by Italy's Georgio Lamberti in
Bonn in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Known for his mastery of middle distance events, Thorpe is also
a world record holder of 400m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
"It is my second world record in short course. I've learned to
accept that. It's not difficult, but you have to get on with your
career. Don't let that stand in your way," Thorpe said after the
final.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on his own performance, the teenager said: "I felt
fine. I produced a very fast 200m in the warm-up and I was quite
excited to do a fast time in the actual event (final). To come
here for a sprint meet was much easier. I did not feel together --
my stroke and my kick were not synchronized and that was somewhat
of a problem.
</P>
<P>
"The short-course world records are probably not as high a
standard as the long-course world records, which take nothing away
from them. But they're a little bit easier," Thorpe said.
</P>
<P>
"I'm still striving for a long-course world record. It makes my
400m freestyle tomorrow very exciting," added Thorpe, who is
looking forward to that and the 4x200m freestlye relay Friday
night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
