<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, April 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav state television on Thursday showed
footage of three captured U.S. soldiers who admitted they were "
captured on Yugoslav territory on March 31."
</P>
<P>
The television identified the three were "officers Andrew
Ramirez and Stone James, and soldier Steven Gonzalez." Three U.S.
Army soldiers on a reconnaissance mission on the Macedonia-
Yugoslavia border were missing Wednesday night after being fired
upon, the U.S. Pentagon officials said. (U.S. Soldiers-Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- A Russian reconnaissance warship will be sent to the
Mediterranean on Friday to ensure the country's security because
NATO is expected to launch its phase-3 aggression against
Yugoslavia, said Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said he had informed U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright of the decision to send the warship there. The warship
will collect information to ensure that Russia can know the all
developments at any time and get itself prepared. Meanwhile,
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev also said on Wednesday that Russia
would soon send seven warships to the region around the Yugoslavia
conflict. (Russia-Warships)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Thursday
instructed Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov to urgently call a meeting
attended by foreign ministers of the Group of Eight major
industrialized nations in a bid to find a political solution to
the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
"The situation threatens to degenerate into a big calamity, and
not just in Europe," Yeltsin said in a statement. "Every wasted
day leads to new losses and new tragedies. We must act immediately,
" said the president. (Russia-Yugoslavia-Yeltsin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Defense Secretary George Robertson said on
Thursday that the NATO campaign in Yugoslavia would be "long and
difficult".
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Britain's Sky television, Robertson said the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) "has the determination and
stomach" to keep on the bombing as long as possible. The air
strike against Yugoslavia stretched into its ninth day on Thursday.
NATO said on Wednesday that the bombing would be intensified and
expanded as a number of new targets had been chosen. (UK-
Yugoslavia) 
</P>
