<HEADLINE> French Communists Remain in Government Despite Dispute on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The French Communist Party (PCF) has
not shown any sign of leaving the Socialist government of Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin, although it strongly opposes France's role
in NATO strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The government ministers from the PCF expressed their concerns
over the bombings by NATO at two cabinet meetings Wednesday and
Thursday, while the Greens and Interior Minister Jean-Pierre
Chevenement, who leads the left-wing group, have also expressed
opposition to the NATO intervention.
</P>
<P>
Jospin admitted on Thursday that France is experiencing a time
of ``crisis and tension,'' but he said the government has to run
the country in a normal way.
</P>
<P>
With a few exceptions, the opposition Gaullist Rally for the
Republic (RPR) and centrist Union for French Democracy (UDF)
supported President Jacques Chirac and the government in joining
the U.S.-led NATO operation.
</P>
<P>
RPR President Philippe Seguin even suggested that Jospin expel
the PCF ministers because, he said, France is ``in a state of war.
''
</P>
<P>
The French constitution, drafted under President Charles de
Gaulle, does not require the president or the government to seek
parliamentary approval before joining a war.
</P>
<P>
Although most French lawmakers support the country's role in
the NATO operation, recent polls on public opinion show that those
who support the NATO action and those who oppose it are equally
divided. enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
