<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Helps Nepal Improve Primary Education System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced
Thursday a credit of 12.5 million U.S. dollars to support Nepal's
basic and primary education program, the bank's Kathmandu Office
said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the credit is the first in a series of adaptable
program loans totaling up to 50 million dollars that the bank
plans to provide over the next 10 years to support Nepal's
education reforms.
</P>
<P>
The 10-year program will focus on strengthening institutional
capacity at national, district and school levels, delivering more
efficient and better quality basic and primary education services
and raising the learning achievements and increasing equitable
access, especially for girls and under-served communities.
</P>
<P>
"The objective is to improve the quality of teaching and
educational results, and work toward extending the basic cycle
from five to eight years," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said the World Bank and the Danish International Development
Agency, the European Union, Finland and Norway will contribute a
total of 106 million dollars to the program.
</P>
<P>
"The expected increase in access to basic and primary education
under the program, combined with higher completion rates resulting
from quality improvement, would result in a 10 percent increase in
net enrollment over the program period," the bank predicted.
</P>
<P>
Though Nepal has announced basic education for all by the year
2000, it has attained only a literacy rate of 42 percent in the
past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
"At present, about 3.2 million children have enrolled in public
and private primary schools across the nation, which is 68 percent
of the total population of school-aged children," said the State
of the Rights of the Child in Nepal in 1998 released by the Child
Workers in Nepal Concerned Center, a non-governmental
organization.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank provided a credit of 30.6 million dollars in
1992 for a basic and primary education project in Nepal, which is
expected to close at the end of this year, the bank added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
