<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Police Separates From Armed Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian State Police
(Polri) Thursday officially separated from the Indonesian Armed
Forces (ABRI), to become an independent force in the country.
</P>
<P>
Defense and Security Minister/ABRI chief Gen. Wiranto, who
attended the separation ceremony at ABRI headquarters here, said,
as of April 1, 1999 the State Police which had been put under the
control of the armed forces since 1966, have become a force under
the organizational purview of the Ministry of Defense and
Security.
</P>
<P>
He said the detachment was the starting point of the
government's efforts to make the police an independent force and
efforts to strengthen democracy in the country.
</P>
<P>
But he also said the detachment did not mean an "absolute
severance" in the structural and cultural links between Polri and
ABRI.
</P>
<P>
Polri's complete separation from ABRI and evolution into a
really independent force required a transitional period of at
least two years, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said although policemen would retain their status as ABRI
members during the transitional period, they were from now on
expected to operate as law enforcers who carry out their duties
without resort to military methods.
</P>
<P>
"Policemen must increasingly abide by the philosophy: fight
crime, love humanity and protect the people," Wiranto noted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Wiranto said, after the separation (of the police from
ABRI), ABRI will only consist of the Army, the Navy and the Air
Force. So, ABRI leaders have proposed to the president to change
the institution's name to Indonesian National Armed Forces (TNI).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indonesian Police chief Gen. Roesmanhadi said the
police will change its educational system starting this coming
academic year and conduct a review of its doctrines and laws.
</P>
<P>
"The present police laws, which use military discipline, will
have to be changed to address civilian values," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
