<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Prisoners to Be Allowed to Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- South African prisoners will
be allowed to vote in this year's general election, the
Constitutional Court ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In its judgement on an application brought on behalf of two
prisoners, the court ruled that it was unconstitutional to deny
prisoners the right to vote and ordered the Independent Electoral
Commission to provide for awaiting-trial and convicted prisoners
to put their names on the voters' roll and to vote on June 2.
</P>
<P>
The ruling only applies to people who are behind bars during
the registration period which began in November last year and
ended on March 15.
</P>
<P>
The ruling extends the franchise to most of South Africa's
146,000 prisoners, a third of them awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
The court said the order excluded people, now in prison, who
were free during the registration periods but failed to register.
</P>
<P>
Certain classes of prisoners had been excluded by law from
voting in the 1994 election but parliament had made no attempt to
introduce similar legislation since 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
