<HEADLINE> U.S. Firms to Design New Guangzhou Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. firms have won the bid
to design the main building of the terminal for Guangzhou's Baiyun
Airport to be relocated, in south China's Guangdong Province, it
was announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The Parsons Corp. and URS Greiner Corp. will collaborate with
the Guangdong Provincial Architectural Design Institute to do the
designing, said Guangzhou Mayor Lin Shusen.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou city government decided to move its Baiyun
Airport, one of China's busiest, to the outskirts away from the
crowded urban area as the airport has been overburdened by
increasing passengers and cargo volume.
</P>
<P>
The design will be completed in October of this year, and
public bidding will then be held for the purchase of equipment,
said Zhang Chunlin, general manger of the Baiyun Airport.
</P>
<P>
At an estimated total cost of 19.5 billion yuan (about 2.3
billion U.S. dollars), the first-phase construction of the airport
will become operational by 2002 and it will be capable of handling
some 70 million arrivals and departures a year when the entire
airport is completed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
