<HEADLINE> Incident-Involved South Korean Ship to Call at Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean container ship,
which sunk a North Korean ship in a collision incident, is
expected to call at the Colombo port Friday, Sri Lanka's official
radio reported Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The 52,000-ton South Korean ship Hyundai Duke will also come
with two rescued North Koreans, said the radio.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's ship-to-shore communication center said the Indian
Air Force had sent a plane from the Andaman Islands to look for
the missing 35 North Koreans from the 7,000-ton Manopok.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the communication center said the collision
happened about 560 kilometers southeast of Sri Lanka at about 9
p.m. Colombo time (1500 GMT) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first collision of ships from the two Koreas in
international waters. The North Korean ship was carrying cement
while the South Korean vessel was ferrying electronics and other
export items on its way to Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
