<HEADLINE> 37 DPRK Sailors Missing After Inter-Korean Ship Collision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 37 sailors from the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) are still missing after their
ship sank Wednesday evening following a collision with a South
Korean Hyundai container ship in the Indian Ocean, said the
Hyundai Merchant Marine Co. on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Hyundai container ship "Hyundai Duke" collided with the
small DPRK vessel "Manpoho" 500 miles from Sri Lanka at about 6:
20 p.m. local time, the first accident between the two nations
since the Korean Peninsula was divided in 1945.
</P>
<P>
The 7,000-ton DPRK cement carrier, with 39 crewmen on board,
sank while the 61,500-ton Hyundai container vessel on its way to
Europe with electronics and other export products, sustained minor
damage.
</P>
<P>
The Hyundai ship continued to look for the missing sailors,
along with a rescue boat dispatched by India at Hyundai's request,
a spokesman of Hyundai Merchant Marine Co said.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the collision has as of yet been released, said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Foreign Affairs-Trade Ministry said it is
trying to get more information regarding the accident through its
diplomatic missions in the region. It has also asked Sri Lanka to
assist in the rescue operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
