CANBERRA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- IOC member Phil Coles was
deprived of his organising role in the 100-day Olympic Torch relay
of the Sydney 2000 Games on Thursday in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
Coles, 67, has all his Sydney Games duties taken away by the
Sydney organising committee SOCOG when the International Olympic
Committee (IOC) invested him for his acceptation of free holidays
in Salt Lake City last month.
</P>
<P>
The former Olympic kayaker now faces a further IOC inquiry over
allegations that he received gold and diamond jewelry from someone
connected with Athens' failed bid for the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
The allegations, which Coles denies, was recognized by Coles'
ex-wife Georgina, who wrote to the IOC two weeks ago that she had
received a gold and diamond necklace and cufflinks from a man
involved in Athens' 1996 bid.
</P>
<P>
Coles has said he received a pair of cufflinks in Athens but
they were not worth any more than 30 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
