<HEADLINE> Nepal to Hold Conference on Harnessing Eastern Himalayan Rivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A two-day conference will begin
here Saturday on regional cooperation in harnessing the eastern
Himalayan rivers, the organizer said in a press release Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This is to be the final dissemination conference as a part of
the joint study undertaken by the Center for Policy Research in
New Delhi, the Bangladesh Unnayan Parishad in Dhaka and the
Institute for Integrated Development Studies of Nepal (IIDS).
</P>
<P>
The IIDS, the organizer of the conference, said that the 86
participants include politicians, academicians, journalists,
representatives of the private sector and experts from India,
Bangladesh and Nepal.
</P>
<P>
It said that under the second phase of the joint study, the
eight studies completed looked at many of the crucial issues
concerning the subjects under study and offered insights and ideas
toward helping solve the problems standing in the way of
strengthened cooperative efforts.
</P>
<P>
"The subjects under study included augmentation of lean season
flow, water quality, regional energy grid, flood disaster
management, dam safety, environment and rehabilitation, seismic
monitoring and inland water transport," the IIDS, a
non-governmental organization, said.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, efforts have been made to exploit waters of the
Ganges, Brahamaputra and Meghna. The Growth Quadrangle comprising
Bangladesh, Bhutan, India and Nepal was initiated in December 1996
for joint efforts in this regard. Foreign secretaries of the four
countries had met on two occasions.
</P>
<P>
The IIDS said that prior to the conference, it will be
organizing an interaction session on Friday on "SAARC Process: How
to Move Forward."
</P>
<P>
Prominent Nepalese experts, high-ranking officials and the
SAARC secretary-general are expected to attend the interaction
along with some prominent persons from India, it said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is to host in November the 11th summit of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), which groups
Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri
Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
