<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BP Amoco Announces Acquisition Of US Arco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- BP Amoco PLC announced Thursday
that it has acquired U.S. oil company Atlantic Richfield (ARCO)
for 26.6 billion dollars in stock, paving the way to become the
world's second largest oil company.
</P>
<P>
The deal is the latest example of consolidation in the oil
industry. BP Amoco has been a leading force in that consolidation.
The former British Petroleum PLC acquired Amoco Corp. of Chicago
for 57.6 billion dollars in December last year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts have hailed the deal as a coup for BP Amoco and
expressed confidence in its ability to save nearly one billion US
dollars in costs from it.
</P>
<P>
Those savings have raised the value of BP Amoco to 170 billion
U.S. dollars compared with a combined market capitalization for
the two firms of around 100 billion US dollars last August when
their merger was announced.
</P>
<P>
However, the deal could fall foul of the regulatory authorities
in Alaska where there is growing concern in the US state's
legislature over BP's potential dominance of Alaska's primary
industry.
</P>
<P>
The 25 billion dollar takeover of Arco will immediately breach
Alaskan statutes which limit a company's right to oil exploration
acreage.
</P>
<P>
Ken Boyd, director of Alaska's Department of Natural Resources,
was quoted as saying, "the takeover of Arco would give the new BP
870,349 acres onshore, well above the 500,000 acre limit."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
