<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SKorea's Forex Reserves Reach 57 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's total foreign currency
reserves rose to a record high of 57.45 billion U.S. dollars at
the end of March from 55.46 billion dollars in February, said the
Bank of Korea on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The total of foreign currency reserves include deposits in
overseas branches of South Korean banks.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's usable foreign currency reserves dipped to 7.26
billion dollars in November 1997 when it borrowed a bailout loan
of 58 billion dollars from the International Monetary Fund to tide
over its foreign exchange crisis caused by corporate bankruptcies
and bad loans of financial institutions in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the rise of foreign exchange
reserves to the steady expansion of the current account surplus
and the inflow of foreign funds arising from asset sales by local
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
