<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Week of Mourning of Genocide Victims Begins in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has
declared a one- week mourning period countrywide in preparation
for the fifth commemoration of the 1994 genocide due on April 7th,
state-run radio announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The week will be marked by low-key activities in Rwanda, with
the organization of conferences, debates, as well as film shows on
genocide in all prefectures of the country. Flags will flying at
half-mast, and the national radio will continually play funeral
music and songs, recalling the terrible sufferings and ordeal
undergone during the 90-day genocide, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Themes to be discussed will focus on the evaluation of the
five-year period after the genocide, what has been so far done to
the victims, the government's strategy to fight the genocidal
ideology, the release of detainees without file cases, and the
role of Rwanda in curbing genocide in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Burial ceremonies of the remains of the victims at identified
massacre sites will take place in different parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
''To remember the people who were brutally massacred during the
April- July genocide is the responsibility of any conscientious
human being,'' said Rwandan Culture Minister Francois Ngarambe.
</P>
<P>
Over half a million of Tutsis and moderate Hutus were
slaughtered during the period.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the week of mourning will culminate into the
official burial of the remains of more than 20,000 Tutsis
massacred at Kibeho Catholic Mission, in Gikongoro, southwest of
the capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
Genocide survivors have taken the opportunity to call for
justice to be done, and compensation paid to the victims. More
than 125,000 genocide suspects are detained in Rwandan prisons.
Rwandan criminal courts which began operating in December 1996
have tried over 1,000 suspects.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two culprits have so far been publicly executed.
</P>
<P>
Frederic Mutagwera, chairman of the ''Ibuka'' (remember)
umbrella organization of 20 associations of genocide survivors,
said ''the evaluation of what has been done in favor of the
survivors and that of actions aimed at fighting the causes of
genocide is positive, but there is a long way to go, notably about
uprooting the culture of impunity.''
</P>
<P>
He said genocide survivors still face insurmountable problems
to be integrated in the socio-economic life like other citizens.
</P>
<P>
Similar programs relating to the commemoration of the 1994
genocide have been organized by communities of Rwandans in the
diaspora, notably in Belgium, Switzerland, Britain, France, the
U.S., and Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Close 1.20 Percent Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks registered
substantial increases across the board Thursday and once again
broke the 11,000 mark since this trading week.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index rose 130.78 points, or 1.20 percent, to
close at 11,072.98 before a five-day Easter break.
</P>
<P>
The increase was brought about by strong gains in Tokyo and
futures-related buying, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
However, the turnover dropped to 3.295 billion HK dollars (422
million U.S. dollars), 742 million HK dollars (95 million U.S.
dollars) lower than Wednesday's turnover of 4.037 billion HK
dollars (517 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Banking shares rose 262.57 points, or 1.56 percent, to close at
17,042.81, while utilities, properties and commerce and industry
gained 0.23 percent, 1.71 percent and 1.11 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The red-chip Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corporations Index went
up 11.77 points, or 1.47 percent, to 811,45, while the H-share
index rose 7.38 points, or 2.09 percent, to 360.19.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index broke the 11,000 point to open at 11,017.45
Thursday, but ended the morning session at 10,991.15. The stocks
climbed in the afternoon to break the 11,000 mark at close.
</P>
</TEXT>
