<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thais to Save 30 Bln Baht Under New Economic Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Thais will save nearly 30 billion
baht (810 million U.S. dollars) annually from tax cuts and reduced
energy costs under the government's new economic stimulus package
announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Power bills in the household sector would drop by 370 million
baht (10 million dollars) a month from April to July, while those
in the commercial and industrial sectors would decline by 1.1
billion baht (29 million dollars) a month and those of other users
would slip by 128 billion baht (3.4 billion dollars), Thai News
Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Local households nationwide could save 187 million baht (5
million dollars) a month on their cooking gas bills, while the
industrial sector could save 42 billion baht (1.1 billion dollars)
a month.
</P>
<P>
The overall savings result from the government's decision to
cut value-added tax from 10 percent to seven percent, excise tax
on fuel oil from 17.5 percent to five percent and reduce income
tax.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, commercial banks welcomed the new economic package,
saying it reflected the government's commitment to pull out the
economy out of the crisis, and pledged to resume lending to local
business communities.
</P>
<P>
Economists said they believed the package could help spur
economic activities and boost the country growth rate to achieve a
conservative target of one percent this year, from a contraction
of eight percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said the government would
introduce further measures to boost Thai exports and tackle
remaining problems in the financial and corporate sectors, two key
areas that are vital to the achievement of Thailand's economic
revival efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
