<HEADLINE> CPC Leader Meets Indian Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Wei Jianxing, member of the
Standing Committee of Political Bureau of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) Central Committee, said today that China would like to
make joint efforts with India to establish the bilateral
constructive partnership oriented towards the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
To advance friendship between China and India, two most
populous countries in the world, reflects the aspiration of the
peoples of the two countries because it is in the interest of the
fundamental interest of the two peoples and beneficial to the
peace and stability in Asia and in the world at large, Wei told
Sitaram Yechury, member of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of India (Marxist) during a meeting here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Wei, also member of the Secretariat of the CPC Central
Committee, noted that China has consistently paid attention to
pursuing good neighborly friendship with India on the basis of the
Five Principles of the Peaceful Co-existence.
</P>
<P>
He added that his last India visit in December 1997 has
impressed him deeply. He asked Yechury to convey his regards to
Harkishan Singh Surjeet, general secretary of the Communist Party
of India (Marxist).
</P>
<P>
He hailed the good relations between the two parties and spoke
highly of Communist Party of India (Marxist)'s contribution to
safeguarding the friendship of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Yechury appreciated great achievements China has made in
various fields under CPC's leadership. He expressed his belief
that headed by CPC, China would reach its objectives set on the
recently-concluded 2nd Session of the 9th National People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his party and the Indian people all cherish
Indian-Chinese friendship and the delegation is aimed at pushing
forward the bilateral friendly ties.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is here at the invitation of CPC.  
</P>
</TEXT>
