<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat in Egypt for Talks on Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
Thursday arrived in Egypt's Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh in
the Sinai Peninsula for a brief visit.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will hold talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on
the latest developments in the Middle East peace process, seeking
ways of breaking the stalemate in the peace-making efforts,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled since
last December when Israel suspended the Wye accord signed last
October after it carried out the first stage of the three-phased
withdrawal from another 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who frequently visits Egypt to consult with Mubarak on
issues related to the peace process, will brief the Egyptian
leader on the outcome of his recent efforts to garner
international support for Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has announced that he would declare an independent
Palestinian state on May 4 when the five-year interim self-rule
period stipulated by the Oslo accords expires.
</P>
<P>
He had visited a number of European countries and the United
States in recent weeks, trying to rally support for the
Palestinian plan and recognition for a future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's efforts have yielded tangible results. The European
Union (EU) issued a statement a week ago saying that the
Palestinians have "unqualified right to self-determination,
including the option of a state," which it expressed readiness to
recognize "in due course." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
