<HEADLINE> Former U.S. President Hopes Indonesia's Election to be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting former U.S. president
Jimmy Carter here Thursday expressed his belief that a free and
fair general election in Indonesia will enhance peace and economic
recovery in the country.
</P>
<P>
Carter, who was here to monitor the preparation for the
upcoming election, made the remarks following a 90-minute meeting
with Indonesian President B.J. Habibie at the Merdeka Palace.
</P>
<P>
He said that nations all over the world expect a free and fair
election in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Carter, however, declined to disclose the topic of his meeting
with Habibie, saying it was not the time for him to do so, because
he will still meet with another agency to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
Carter came here Wednesday with his wife, Rosalynn, for a
two-day visit. He met with Foreign Minister Ali Alatas Thursday
morning. He is also scheduled to meet with leaders of some
political parties and members of the General Election Commission
(KPU).
</P>
<P>
Indonesia will hold its first multi-party general election in
30 years on June 7 during which 48 parties are preparing to
contest for 500 seats of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
The election is expected to be monitored by different quarters
including an international general election monitoring team led by
Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
Officials said earlier, foreign observers sent by the Carter
Center will arrive here three or four days before the election.
</P>
<P>
Carter is due to leave Jakarta on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
