<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Light Industry Export Targeted to Grow 4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- China's light industry will try to
earn its targeted profits of 56 billion U.S. dollars in exports
this year or achieve a growth of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Due to the lingering Asian financial crisis and the global
economic slowdown, boosting exports in the sector will become
tougher this year.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Tao, deputy director of the State Administration of Light
Industry (SALI), said that China will adopt a series of measures
to encourage the export of profit-making products by upgrading
technology and improving quality.
</P>
<P>
He said that products such as leather, handicrafts, plastics,
hardware, household electric appliances and ceramics will be given
priority.
</P>
<P>
"The sector will undergo further restructuring to increase
technology and meet the demands of the ever-changing global market,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
China will take positive measures to encourage the booming
processing sector to set up factories and increase sales outlets
in other countries as an effective way to open up export channels.
</P>
<P>
Currently, a number of famous Chinese enterprises have
established footholds in foreign markets, for instance, the
Jiangsu-based Chun Lan Group has sold complete sets of equipment
for making air conditioners to Russia, and the Shanghai-based "
Hero Pen" company has established factories in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
An official with SALI said that the sector made progress in
promoting market diversification last year, pointing out that 80
percent of exports went to the United States, European and
Hongkong markets.
</P>
<P>
She also said that China will continue to boost exports to
these traditional markets this year, and at the same time, more
efforts will be made to tap new markets such as the Russian, East
European, Latin American and African markets.
</P>
<P>
The sector's export volume reached 54.9 billion U.S. dollars
last year, up 3.04 percent from 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
