<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
Thursday limped to a higher close in a truncated session ahead of
the Easter long weekend, drawing support from a surge in the
Japanese market.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market opened lower after the Dow Jones
Industrial Average on Wall Street dropped 127.10 points to 9786.16
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index, which closed at ahead of the four-day
holiday, finished 6.2 points, or 0.21 percent, higher at 2973.4,
off a high of 2977.6 and a low of 2950.2.
</P>
<P>
"It's fairly quiet. We were looking down early, taking our lead
from the U.S.," dealer Hamish Dee of Henderson Charlton Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese market is doing well though, and the Hong Kong
market is looking better as well.
</P>
<P>
"I think we've drawn a little bit of comfort from that."
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, share prices closed the morning higher on active
buying by foreign investors, reflecting growing optimism about the
near-term outlook for the Japanese market, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed 14.9 points higher at 5346.7
and the all resources index closed 2.2 points lower at 1033.6.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was thin because of the shortened trading
session Thursday, with 224.13 million shares traded valued at
678.24 million Australian dollars (427.29 million U.S. dollars).
Falls outnumbered rises 504 to 421, with 355 steady.
</P>
<P>
Topping volume was Trans Global Resources with a turnover of
36.74 million shares, and its share price closed 0.2 of a cent
higher at 3.4 cents.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank gained five cents, Commonwealth Bank
gained 25.1 cents, ANZ Banking Group dipped four cents and Westpac
Banking Corp gained eight cents.
</P>
<P>
Market heavyweight and global media giant News Corp rose 2.8
cents while its preferred scrip lifted 6.6 cents.
</P>
<P>
Telstra Corp added 8.3 cents, its rival, Cable &AMP; Wireless
Optus, was steady at 3.67 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among resources, hammered Wednesday by a plunge in commodity
prices at London Metal Exchange, BHP gained 11.5 cents, Rio Tinto
dropped 27.7 cents and WMC gained three cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 1.7 points, or 0.17 percent, weaker at
987.6, Sydney trade in gold bullion was up 0.50 at 280.25 U.S.
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
