<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Export Earnings to Drop: Economists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is not expected to earn as
much from exports as it did last year because of reduced exports
in textile, sugar and cement and low copper sales.
</P>
<P>
A report on the first quarter of 1999 prepared by an economist
intelligence unit said Thursday that higher exports to Europe were
expected in horti and floricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Although Finance Minister Edith Nawakwi predicted a 15 percent
increase in non-traditional export earnings in 1999, total
earnings were likely to be lower, it predicted.
</P>
<P>
"Even if non-traditional export revenue does grow, total export
earnings in 1999 are unlikely to be much higher when copper export
earnings, which account for some 75 percent of the total, are
unlikely to increase much," the report says.
</P>
<P>
Prospects of increased exports in textile, sugar and cement to
central Africa would remain subdued because of continuing
political instability there.
</P>
<P>
Growth in imported expenditure was expected because of demands
of new investors in the copper mines and an anticipated increase
in imported agricultural equipment following the scrapping of
duty.
</P>
<P>
The increase is also attributed to an impending salary rises in
the civil service and the relative stability in the value of the
local currency kwacha.
</P>
<P>
"Although donor funding will boost invisible inflow into Zambia
in the form of current transfers this will be offset by increased
expenditure on imported services associated with new investment in
the country's copper mines," said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report also forecast that Zambia's current account deficit
would widen to 410 million U.S. dollars this year and narrow down
to 192 million dollars in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The report expects the exchange rate to stabilize with the
kwacha depreciating to 2,928 to one dollar at the end of 1999 and
3,210 to the dollar in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The report describes the four percent growth announced by the
Finance Minister in the 1999 Budget as optimistic and over
ambitious.
</P>
<P>
Zambia should not expect an increase in copper production even
if the mines were sold as planned because actual production would
only take off between 2000 and 2001, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
