<HEADLINE> Demand for Bangladeshi Workers Abroad May Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The demand for Bangladeshi workers
in foreign countries may decline in the coming years, producing an
unfavorable impact on the inward remittances by Bangladeshi
workers abroad.
</P>
<P>
A total of 267,667 Bangladeshi workers, both skilled and
unskilled, got employment in 15 countries last year, about 30
percent down from 381,077 employment in the previous year, The
Financial Express daily newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asia, once the major employment destination for
Bangladeshi workers abroad, has lost its position due to an
economic recession there following a financial turmoil in the
region in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, once the largest provider of employment to
Bangladeshi citizens overseas, employed only 551 Bangladeshi
workers in 1998, a sharp decrease from 152,844 workers employed in
1997.
</P>
<P>
During the first two months this year, expatriate Bangladeshis
sent back only 260 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi workers abroad remitted about 1.59 billion dollars
in 1998, and about 1.53 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the highest amount of remittance was sent from
expatriate Bangladeshis in Saudi Arabia, followed by the Untied
Arab Emirates, Kuwait and Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Starts Destination Inspection of Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Nigeria Customs Service (NCS)
will officially do away with the services of pre-shipment
inspections and will begin "Destination Inspection of Imports" as
from April 1.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Ahmed Mustapha, comptroller-general of the customs
service, told reporters in capital Abuja Wednesday that the
introduction of the new system was in line with the 1999 budget
speech by Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalami Abubakar, New
Nigerian paper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar said in the speech that the pre-shipment inspection of
imports into the country would be phased out with effect as from
April 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
Mustapha said all the reforms were directed toward achieving
greater trade facilitation and revenue generation without
compromising accountability and transparency.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government, he noted, decided to abolish the
pre-shipment inspection scheme introduced in 1976 as it found that
the scheme created more problems than the ones it was intended to
solve.
</P>
<P>
Destination inspection of imports would lead to "tremendous
rise in revenue collection" because in the past the government had
to pay huge amount of foreign currency for the services of the
inspectors outside the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mustapha stressed that the better part of the new scheme was
the preparedness of the Nigeria Customs Service to give quick
clearance within 48 hours which has been put in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
