<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Stone Library Gets Donations from Outside China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The decision of China's cultural
relics authorities to put some 1,000-year-old Buddhist stone
tablets with inscriptions in their original caves has got a good
response from donors.
</P>
<P>
The Restoration Organizing Committee of Stone Scriptures at
Beijing's Yunju Temple today accepted 5.5 million yuan (662,000 U.
S. dollars) worth of donations.
</P>
<P>
Yunju Temple is in a suburban area of Beijing. It has 14,278
stone slabs carved with scriptures from the Sui Dynasty (581-618)
to the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644), 22,000 volumes of scriptures on
paper from the Ming, and 77,000 wooden blocks with scriptures from
the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
Buddhism came to China from India about 2,000 years ago. Both
scholars and common people regard the temple and its Buddhist
relics as Beijing's Dunhuang, a reference to the site of famous
grottoes in northwestern Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
Preserving these stone scriptures is important to Buddhists,
scholars, and common people as well, according to Shan Jixiang,
vice-chairman of the committee.
</P>
<P>
China started uncovering the stone scriptures in 1956 in
commemoration of the 2,500th anniversary of the birth of Sakyamuni,
the founder of Buddhism. But, because of the type of stone and air
pollution over a long period of time, many of them are seriously
corroded.
</P>
<P>
Between the Sui and Tang (618-907) dynasties, Jing Wan, a
Buddhist monk, built a temple for the stone inscriptions to
preserve Buddhist classicals during the wars of the time.
</P>
<P>
The Yonghe Temple, another famous Buddhist site in downtown
Beijing, has put some stone slabs on exhibit for visitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Confirms 3 U.S. Soldiers Seized by Yugoslav forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, April 1 (Xinhua) -- North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) spokesman Jamie Shea said here Thursday that
three US soldiers who went missing Tuesday afternoon had been
captured by Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed it in a statement, saying the capture was
indicated by some TV pictures this morning. But he gave no details
about the TV reports.
</P>
<P>
Shea said the three US soldiers serving under NATO Command as
part of the NATO-led force in the Former Yugoslav Republic of
Macedonia which is preparing for a peacekeeping mission went
missing "along the border between Yugoslavia and the Former
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia".
</P>
<P>
The NATO spokesman stressed that all NATO forces in Macedonia
are there "in the context of a peacekeeping mission. They pose
absolutely no threat to Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said the NATO expects that any soldier that
happen to be captured by the Yugoslav armed forces "must be
treated in a humane way in accordance with international civilized
norms of Behavior."
</P>
<P>
Three U.S. Army soldiers on a reconnaissance mission on the
Macedonia-Yugoslavia border were missing Wednesday night after
being fired upon, the U.S. Pentagon officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
