<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaunda Declared Stateless by Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Former Zambian president Kenneth
Kaunda has been declared stateless by the Ndola High Court, media
reports here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In his landmark judgement Wednesday, Judge Chalendo Sakala
ordered the citizenship Board of Zambia to quash the Zambian
nationality of Kaunda, who had been ruling the country since its
independence in 1964 until 1991, when he was defeated by current
President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Sakala said the then acting Home Affairs Minister John
Mwanakatwe made a "serious error" in 1970 when he granted Kaunda
Zambian citizenship because at no time did Kaunda apply for
Zambian citizenship.
</P>
<P>
He said Kaunda, who was absent from court, ruled Zambia legally
as a Malawian only in the first term which ended in 1968.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was required by law to apply for Zambian citizenship a
year after Zambia's independence, Zambia Daily Mail said.
</P>
<P>
According to a letter read out in court, Mwanakatwe granted
Kaunda citizenship because the former president was unaware of
his nationality status.
</P>
<P>
The judgement means Kaunda, who was born of Malawian parents,
is neither a Zambia nor a Malawian.
</P>
<P>
After the judgement, Kaunda's lawyers Patrick mvunga and
Mwangala Zaloumis appealed to the Supreme Court for a stay of
execution for the order to quash Kaunda's Zambian citizenship.
</P>
<P>
Sakala granted the stay.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda's lawyers told the press after the ruling that the
judgement will have a telling effect on the nation.
</P>
<P>
Former Legal Affairs Minister Remmy Mushota and
ex-parliamentarian Patrick Katyoke presented their petition in
1997 for having Kaunda declared a stateless citizen, arguing that
Kaunda ruled the country fraudulently.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was barred from running for the country's presidency in
the elections held in 1996, when a constitutional amendment was
adopted under which foreign nationals and those with foreign
parentage are prohibited from contesting the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda has vowed to contest the post in the next elections in
2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Moves to Reduce Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has taken measures to
force factories to adopt cleaner technology over the next two
years and restrict vehicles entering Bangkok's major roads, senior
Thai officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Rachada Singalavanija, deputy director-general of the Industry
Ministry's Department of Industrial Works, said the new
enforcement was aimed at ensuring minimum emission and waste
generating by local factories and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Incentives would be employed to encourage local firms to reduce
pollution, or they would be forced to pay for the pollution they
create, he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The new measures, which would be contained in amendments to the
1992 Industrial Work Act, include the introduction of an emission
charge to be imposed based on the amount of pollution or waste
generated, and a pollution management fee to be imposed on
factories that fail to meet the legal requirement, Rachada said.
</P>
<P>
The amendments, which are in line with objectives of Thailand's
Eighth National Economic and Social Development Plan, were
expected to take effect by 2002, the last year of the five-year
national plan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bangkok Metropolitan Administration (BMA)
claimed its success in an initial effort to reduce air pollution
in metropolitan areas by imposing a zoning-restriction program,
banning vehicles from entering three main roads -- Silom,
Rajprarop and Paholyothin -- in certain times.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey found that the amount of air pollution on
Rajprorop Road decreased to 80-100 micrograms/cubic meter from 242
micrograms/cubic meter before the campaign; on Silom Road to 50-90
micrograms/cubic meter, from 195; and on Paholyothin Road to 65-75
micrograms/cubic meter, from 395, BMA's Deputy City Clerk Wanchart
Supajaturat said.
</P>
<P>
According to the international standard, the safe amount of air
pollution should not exceed 120 micrograms/cubic meter.
</P>
<P>
The BMA would not issue legal measures to enforce the zoning
restriction due to good cooperation from the public and the
program would not be extended to other roads because no other
areas were found to have air pollution exceeding the standard
level, said Wanchart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
