<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thirsty Tanzania Wastes Nearly Half of Processed Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Though many of its residents
have no access to water, Tanzania is losing 72 million shillings
(about 104,347.8 U. S. dollars) daily due to illegal water tapping
and leakage from dilapidated pipelines in its Urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The loss equals to about half of the 523,000 cubic meters of
portable water generated throughout the country in a day, The
African newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a report by Professor Damas Mashauri of the Dar es
Salaam University as saying that this loss of revenue was the main
cause of inefficiency in water supply in the country.
</P>
<P>
Mashauri made the remarks Wednesday at a roundtable discussion
here on water shortage that was attended by industrialists, the
World Bank officials, the business community and scholars.
</P>
<P>
The attendants called for appropriate pricing that matches the
quality and quantity of water supplied in a bid to discard the
notion that water is a free natural resource and freely supplied.
</P>
<P>
The forum also blamed the Dar es Salaam Water and Sanitation
Authority and the Ministry of Water for poor management, urging
immediate privatization of the water supply authorities.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank representative in the country, Ronald Brigish,
said his office is working with the Tanzanian government to
identify a private operator to run water service provision on
tariff basis in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Brigish said, however, it is hard at the moment to locate a
wholesale operator due to the water authority's huge debts and
outdated equipment installations.
</P>
<P>
"Even with the new private operator it will take another five
to six years to establish smooth water supply system in the city,"
the official added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
