<HEADLINE> Turkey Accused of Harming Yugoslav Sovereignty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav ambassador to Ankara,
Darko Tanascovic, has accused Turkey of harming Yugoslavia's
territorial integrity and sovereignty by joining in NATO military
actions.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Daily News published Thursday,
Tanascovic said that by taking part in NATO military operations
against Yugoslavia, it was practically working against
Yugoslavia's territorial integrity and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
This was contradictory to Turkey's repeatedly expressed support
for Yugoslavia's territorial integrity, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Turkey might believe that granting the status of a
third autonomous republic to Kosovo within Yugoslavia's
territorial integrity could be a solution to the problem, but such
a solution could not work because it would not stop the
independent ambitions of the Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador called on Turkey to re-evaluate its
participation in NATO's air strikes against Yugoslavia, which
entered their eighth day Thursday and contributed in part to the
crisis now unfolding in the Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral relations between Turkey and Yugoslavia could be
repaired if Ankara is to change its position, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Tanascovic also accused the Untied States and Britain of being
the leaders of a campaign aimed at dividing Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He denied reports of mass massacres of Kosovo civilians by
Serbian forces, saying that the reports were the product of a
well-organized propaganda machine aiming to justify the NATO air
strikes on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a member state of NATO, supports the military
alliance's bombings against Yugoslavia to pressure President
Slobedan Milosevic into allowing NATO forces into Kosovo to police
a peace deal that would give broad autonomy to ethnic Albanians
who make up 90 percent of the population there.
</P>
<P>
A total of 11 Turkish warplanes stationed in the NATO bases in
Italy, have joined the NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
