<HEADLINE> UAE Expects Increase in GDP in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirate (UAE)
expects its gross domestic product (GDP) to increase this year
despite the impact of depressed oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Oil revenues represent more than 70 percent of the UAE income,
therefore it cannot avoid the impact of the oil prices fall, the
Khaleej Times daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, due to the expected improvement in oil prices, the
UAE's GDP is expected to increase from 170 billion dirhams (about
46.5 billion U.S. dollars) to 176 billion dirhams (about 48.1
billion dollars) in 1999, the paper quoted UAE Minister of
Planning Shaikh Humaid bin Ahmed Al Mualla as saying.
</P>
<P>
Gulf Arab oil ministers recently announced a total oil output
cut of over 900,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Al Mualla said that the UAE's exports of oil products
witnessed a sharp decline from 24 billion dirhams (about 6.6
billion U.S. dollars) in 1997 to 8.4 billion dirhams (about 2.3
billion U.S. dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
He said the GDP had a marginal decline to 170 billion dirhams
(about 46.5 billion dollars) in 1998 from 180 billion dirhams
(about 49.2 billion dollars) in 1996 as oil prices fell by 37
percent during this period.
</P>
<P>
He said consistent attempts are now being made to develop
non-oil revenues, and "we promise an accelerated program of
restructuring."
</P>
<P>
The measures being taken involve slashing government
expenditure and increasing government service fees.
</P>
<P>
"We have adopted certain economic and financial policies to
cope with low crude oil prices and weak demand for petroleum
products," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the UAE economic outlook seems to be very positive.
</P>
<P>
"A clear indication of that is the increase in the final
consumption figures from 112.3 billion dirhams (about 30.7
billion dollars) in 1996 to 114.3 billion dirhams (about 31.2
billion dollars) in 1997 and 119.3 billion dirhams (about 32.6
billion dollars) in 1998," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
