<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lake Polluters Face 30-Day Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Serious polluters around the
Dianchi Lake in southwest China's Yunnan province face compulsory
shutdown of their businesses if they fail to meet the tight
restrictions imposed to transform the lake in time for the opening
of the World Horticulture Exposition which starts early May.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say there are 253 such organizations allowing
outfalls of serious pollution into China's sixth largest
freshwater lake and they have only until May 1st to comply with
the stricter rules.
</P>
<P>
Chinese authorities have insisted businesses stop polluting the
lake, which covers an area of 307 square kilometers, before the
expo, according to an official from the State Environmental
Protection Administration.
</P>
<P>
So far, among the 253 enterprises listed as major polluters in
the area, 150 have passed inspections by environmental protection
agencies, 50 have introduced pollution control systems and another
50 are awaiting inspection, said the official.
</P>
<P>
However, three enterprises have not even started to take any
pollution control action yet and are being closely watched, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Now, from today to May 5, a monitoring center in Kunming, the
provincial capital, will receive and deal with reports from the
public about the pollution situation.
</P>
<P>
The famous lake, located on a high plateau, plays a key role in
balancing the ecological environment in Kunming but has been
seriously polluted by industrial and urban waste water.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Chinese government listed Dianchi Lake as one of
the key projects to be tackled in the "three rivers and three
lakes" project, which also covers Liaohe, Huaihe and Haihe rivers
and Taihu, Chaohu and Dianchi lakes.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has spent more than three billion yuan (
about 400 million US dollars) to clean up the lake, including
loans of 150 million US dollars from the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
