<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Commission Backs Kenyan Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission will give
140 million shillings (about 2.2 million U.S. dollars) to the
Kenya Tourism Board as part of its effort to revamp the tourist
sector in the country.
</P>
<P>
Lutz Salzman, a delegate of the European Commission mission in
Kenyan, announced Wednesday in Mombasa, a coastal city in southern
Kenya, that his mission would establish an endowment fund for
Kenya Tourism Board with a capital investment of 980 million
shillings.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the tourism sector in Kenya which is facing a
major crisis due to long-and short-term structural problems,
needed support from all stake-holders, saying that the annual
earnings from the capital fund would be used to carry out
marketing campaigns for identifying the marketing strategy and
plan.
</P>
<P>
Salzman said the European Commission would also assist the
tourism sector to introduce cruise tourism, which might
significantly contribute to the recovery of the industry.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the success of the cruise tourism would depend
on safe and efficient bathing facilities at the Kenya Ports
Authority coupled by good customer service.
</P>
<P>
Eliud Mahihu, chairman of the Kenya Tourism Board, hailed the
establishment of the capital as supplementary funds to his tourist
board, which had managed to implement marketing campaigns in
Europe with advertisements placed in 46 consumer magazines.
</P>
</TEXT>
