<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Standardizes Auto Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- New automobile insurance
regulations issued by China's Insurance Regulatory Commission (
CIRC) came into force today in Beijing and Shenzhen in Guangdong
Province, partly in a bid to stamp out forged documents.
</P>
<P>
The new rules set the national standards for premiums and
detail the contents of additional insurance cover which will be
observed by all insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with international practice, each driver of a car
has to be insured and policies will be issued under the
supervision of the CIRC. They are forgery-proof and easily
identified with bar-codes and using the English language in
certain sections.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Huaili, deputy general manager of the People's Insurance
Company of China Beijing Branch, said the new regulations will
prevent the use of forged insurance documents.
</P>
<P>
The branch has launched initiatives such as making phone calls
and door to door inquiries to ensure that car owners have
correctly completed insurance application forms and have
officially approved policies.
</P>
<P>
In the first three months of the year, the branch's revenue
from auto insurance premiums went up by 36 percent from the same
period last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought-Stricken Zhuhai Ensures Water Supply to Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The coastal city of Zhuhai in south
China's Guangdong Province faces mounting water shortages, and yet
it tries its best to ensure water supply to nearby Macao,
according to the city's Mayor Huang Longyun.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing dry spell in most of Guangdong province has now
forced officials to ration water between 17:00 and 22:00 each day
when normal supplies are available. The amount is reduced outside
of that core time.
</P>
<P>
Rain has not fallen for more than 200 days and the area only
has a total reservoir water storage of 13.2 million cu.m, which is
only topped up each day by river sources with about 2.0 million cu.
m
</P>
<P>
The Zhuhai Urban Water Supply Company revealed that the city
has 400,000 tons of water for its own daily use and pipes a
further 150,000 tons daily to Macao. An official said that the
company's staff have now been mobilized to help keep sea water
from pouring into the depleted reservoirs that supply water to
Macao.
</P>
<P>
Huang has pledged that the city will continue to shoulder the
responsibility of guaranteeing the amount and the quality of water
supply to Macao, which is the main reason it has restricted
supplies to its own citizens while the shortage continues.
</P>
<P>
Historically, Macao has always been short of fresh water as
there are no rivers feeding its two small reservoirs, which only
hold about one million cu.m at most. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
