<HEADLINE> Former Lebanese Premier to Face Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Former Lebanese Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri and three of his ministers could face judicial
investigations over alleged public funds squandering, the Daily
Star reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Auditing Department claimed that 554 billion
Lebanese pounds (about 360 million U.S. dollars) of the
Independent Municipal Fund were missing under Hariri's
administration which left the office last November.
</P>
<P>
Also, a considerable sum of money collected by the
municipalities from various fees, such as those for electricity,
water and customs duties, was reported missing.
</P>
<P>
The 157-page report, which was submitted to the weekly cabinet
session on Wednesday, suggested that all ministers directly
involved in the case be put under questioning.
</P>
<P>
The probe will cover former Minister of State for Finance Fuad
Saniora, former Minister of Rural Affairs Hagop Demerdjian and his
successor Bassem Al-Sabaa.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has decided to refer the case to the state
prosecutor's office, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
This will be the third probe into former government officials
since Lebanese President Emile Lahoud, who vowed to combat
rampant official corruptions, was elected to the presidency last
October.
</P>
<P>
Former Oil Minister Shahe Barsumian and other nine senior
officials were arrested last month for alleged illegal resale of
imported oil, which stripped the treasury of a total of 800 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the judicial authorities found that a large number
of valuable artifacts were stolen from the country's museums and
national heritage warehouses under the former administration and
are trying to retrieve them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
