<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Hold Securities Law Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- China will hold a nationwide
contest on Securities Law as part of effort to help Chinese
citizens study and understand the law which can be used to protect
their legitimate rights.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Securities reported that the contest will be
sponsored by the General Office of the National People's Congress
(NPC) Standing Committee, the NPC Financial and Economic
Committees, the Commission of Legislative Affairs of the NPC
Standing Committee, China Securities Regulatory Commission, China
Securities and China Central TV (CCTV).
</P>
<P>
The test questions will be carried by China Securities and
Shanghai Securities News on April 8, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Securities Law, the first of its kind, was adopted by the
National People's Congress Standing Committee, China's highest
legislative body, on December 29 last year and will take effect on
July 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The 12-chapter, 214-article law governs all aspects of the
securities industry ranging from securities trading to purchases
of listed companies, to stock exchanges and securities companies,
as well as registration, account settlement and trading services
agencies, self-disciplinary associations, government regulatory
bodies and liabilities for violations of the law.
</P>
<P>
The law prohibits foreign capital from entering the nation's A-
share market.
</P>
<P>
It provides for a two-tier system for the securities industry
and requires securities companies to separate client and internal
accounts. Securities companies are separated from banking, trust
and insurance operations according to the law.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers formulated the law in line with lessons learned from
the Asian financial and stock market crisis. The law contains
detailed stipulations for preventing market risk and standardizing
market operations to protect the interests of investors.
</P>
<P>
Some 38 million Chinese citizens have invested in the nation's
securities market. The Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges have
827 listed companies with total assets over 2,000 billion yuan.
Related companies account for 23.4 percent of the nation total GDP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Develop Resin Automobile Molds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
developed resin automobile molds which will help solve problems
related to time required and high production costs.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts say the development will facilitate the
development of types of automobiles. They also expect the
technology to improve the appearance of domestically manufactured
models.
</P>
<P>
The fact that China's mold production technology has lagged
behind the overall development of the automobile industry has
forced many Chinese automakers to depend heavily on imported molds.
</P>
<P>
Technicians with the Mold Center at the First Automobile Works
(FAW) Group and researchers from Jilin University have developed
12 resin molds for Red Flag limousines. The use of resins in
automobile molds has reduced production time by 50 percent and
costs by as much as 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experiments with the molds have yielded positive results. The
Technology Committee under the National Mold Industry Association
plans to recommend the molds for classification as new national
products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
