<P>
"NATO's attacks on Yugoslavia, using the disproportionate force
of bombers and missiles, constitute unilateral aggression against
a sovereign country, without authorization of the United Nations
Security Council," A. Preskar said in his letter to the editor.
</P>
<P>
The biggest military force on Earth is once again using the
Balkan region for testing its "new weaponry against a small and
helpless, sanctions-struck country", he added.
</P>
<P>
Preskar strongly accuses NATO of targeting water filtering
plants, schools, car factories, housing units and cultural
heritage sites protected by UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
"NATO has no right to play God. The attacks on a sovereign
country must be stopped. If the world allows this to go on, who
will be the next in NATO's hunger for funds and power?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Robert Moyich said in his letter that NATO's airstrikes against
 Yugoslavia is an "illegitimate act of aggression against a
sovereign country".
</P>
<P>
He condemned NATO for using Yugoslavia as a training ground for
 testing its new weaponry.
</P>
<P>
J. Sanders said in his letter that the bombing of Serbia by the
 United States and Britain is a "crime".
</P>
<P>
He noted that the air-raids by NATO "will solve nothing, but
only sweep the problems under the carpet".
</P>
<P>
Steven Sedley asked in his letter that how can anyone think
that destroying cities, killing people from the air, will resolve
conflicts? 
</P>
</TEXT>
