<HEADLINE> Kenyan Anti-Graft Chief Outlines Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's key institutions including
the Judiciary and the Attorney-General's Chamber will be the
targets of the Kenyan Anti-Corruption Authority (KACA), according
to the authority's new director Justice Aaron Ringera.
</P>
<P>
Ringera, who was appointed last week by President Daniel arap
Moi, said Wednesday that he would investigate, arrest and
expeditiously prosecute all cases of corruption, with high level
deals receiving priority.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that he would act on the parliamentary public
accounts and investment committee reports where there was prima
facie evidence of corruption. He would also institute civil suits
in courts for recovery of public funds which were embezzled or
stolen.
</P>
<P>
According to Thursday's Daily Nation newspaper, the anti-graft
director would also target the investigative and prosecution arms
of the police, prisons, all public registries, health, education,
public procurement of goods, revenue services and parastatal
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Ringera had personal assurance of President Moi of full support
in efforts to fight crimes and called on Kenyans to shed their
cynicism with respect to anti-corruption efforts and embrace the
struggle against corruption as a noble and winnable war.
</P>
<P>
The chief also pledged that he would make recommendations,
including adoption of legally enforceable code of conduct, to
enhance management, accountability, transparency and integrity in
the private and public sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
