<HEADLINE> China Drafting Regulations on Jury System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- China is drafting regulations on a
"people's juror system" in an effort to improve the legal
procedure which allows public participation in courtrooms, a
senior judge disclosed here today.
</P>
<P>
"The regulations are expected to be promulgated soon to help
ensure justice," said Zhou Daoluan, a member of the Advisory
Committee of the Supreme People's Court, in an article published
by the Beijing-based Procuratorial Daily.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the shortcomings in the exisiting mechanism, Zhou,
also a well-known law professor, emphasized the necessity of the
regulations.
</P>
<P>
"The regulations will include rules confirming the
qualifications of such jurors, setting educational, ethical and
professional standards for them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also under consideration are selection procedures in which the
candidates are to be nominated by courts and appointed by
legislature, according to the professor.
</P>
<P>
The regulations will also cover the duties and rights of jurors,
the scope of the legal cases they shall be involved with, and look
at their training and welfare needs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
