<HEADLINE> Japan to Develop Spy Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Japan will develop four information-
gathering satellites on its own and the government plans to launch
by fiscal 2002 to boost the country's reconnaissance capability, a
senior government official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that it is beneficial to basically develop them by
using our own technology," Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka
told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Japan's technology is sophisticated enough to develop the
satellites, and maintenance would be easier if they were developed
domestically, the top Japanese government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Some members of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party had said
that Japan should import satellites to save time.
</P>
<P>
Nonaka said the government established a new panel Thursday to
discuss the basic policies on the introduction of the satellites
and the ways to establish organizations and provide facilities
needed to maintain them.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the Japanese government, taking advantage of the
firing of a rocket by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (
DPRK) last August, approved the plan to launch the satellites by
fiscal 2002.
</P>
<P>
Part of the rocket, which Japan claimed as a ballistic missile,
flew over Japan's territory before plunging into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
