<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- This is the third in a question
and answer series on the ABCs of the Basic Law of the Macao
Special Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
 (3) What are the Chinese Government's basic policies
concerning the Macao question?
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government's basic policies concerning the Macao
question are fully spelled out in the Government of the People's
Republic of China Elaboration on Basic Policies Regarding Macao,
an annex to the Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration on Macao.
</P>
<P>
The policies contain the following stipulations:
</P>
<P>
The MSAR of the People's Republic of China will be established
upon China's resumption of exercise of sovereignty over Macao;
</P>
<P>
The MSAR will be directly under the authority of the Central
People's Government and will enjoy a high degree of autonomy,
except in foreign and defense affairs;
</P>
<P>
The government and legislature of the MSAR will be composed of
local residents. Macao's current social and economic systems, as
well as the existing way of life, will remain unchanged;
</P>
<P>
Existing laws will remain basically unchanged. The MSAR will
have the authority to formulate policies in the fields of culture,
science and technology, education and protect cultural relics in
accordance with law;
</P>
<P>
The MSAR will have the authority to maintain and develop
economic and cultural relations and in this context conclude
agreements with states, regions and relevant international
organizations under the name "Macao, China";
</P>
<P>
The MSAR will remain a free port and a separate customs
territory in order to develop economic activities. It will
maintain independent finances and be responsible for maintaining
internal public order; and
</P>
<P>
Apart from displaying the national flag and national emblem of
the People's Republic of China, the MSAR may also display its own
regional flag and emblem.
</P>
<P>
The annex clearly stipulates that the policies of the Chinese
Government on Macao will be contained in the Basic Law of the
Macao Special Administrative Region adopted by the National
People's Congress of the People's Republic of China and these
policies will remain unchanged for 50 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- This is the fourth in a question
and answer series on the ABCs of the Basic Law of the Macao
Special Administrative Region (MSAR):
</P>
<P>
4. Why was it necessary to enact the Basic Law of the Macao SAR?
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration on the Macao Question is
a bilateral international agreement. The Joint Declaration is
binding on both the Chinese and Portuguese governments, but is not
a domestic Chinese law.
</P>
<P>
The basic policies on Macao outlined by the Chinese Government
in the Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration and Annex I are general
and abstract in nature.
</P>
<P>
In view of this, the Chinese Government stated in both the Sino-
Portuguese Joint Declaration and its Annex I that the basic
policies of the People's Republic of China on Macao will be
stipulated in the Basic Law by the National People's Congress and
will remain unchanged for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Chinese Government is committed to enacting the
Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The purpose is to codify and institutionalize the policy of "
one country, two systems" affirmed in the Sino-Portuguese Joint
Declaration and Annex I in the form of domestic law. So doing will
fully guarantee the implementation of China's basic policies
regarding Macao with the coercive power of law. In this sense, the
policy of "one country, two systems" provides the policy basis for
enacting the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The National People's Congress amended China's Constitution
and added Article 31 in December 1984. The article clearly
stipulates: "The State will establish special administrative
regions when necessary. The systems to be instituted in special
administrative regions will be prescribed by laws enacted by the
National People's Congress in light of the specific conditions."
</P>
<P>
This article provides both constitutional guarantees for
implementing the policy of "one country, two systems" and the
constitutional basis for enacting the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, the provisions in China's Constitution
concerning the supreme organ of State power, the highest
administrative office, the highest military office and state
sovereignty, unification and territorial integrity represented the
constitutional basis for enacting the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law is based on the aforementioned provisions which
fully and accurately embody the policy of "one country, two
systems" and safeguard China's unification.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sakyamuni's Sariras Displayed in Beijing's Downtown Lamasery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Relics and remains of Sakyamuni
Buddha and two sariras went on display in the Yonghe Lamasery in
Beijing today as well as ancient genuine stone tablets bearing
religious scriptures.
</P>
<P>
A grand religious ceremony was held to mark the launch of the
exhibition at the Lamasery, China's biggest Tibetan monastery.
</P>
<P>
The two sariras were first found in a cave of the Yunju Temple,
Beijing's suburban Fangshan District, in 1981 and were stored in
the suburban temple for most of the time.
</P>
<P>
Yunju Temple, a well-known Buddhist shrine in north China and
built in 631 during Tang Dynasty (618-907), also houses more than
14,000 pieces of inscribed religious stone tablets that were
inscribed by Chinese monks.
</P>
<P>
Also on display are a number of genuine stone tablets bearing
Khitan Tripitaka -- translated teachings of the Buddha and
translated treatises, mainly commentaries by eminent monks -- as
well as documents, pictures and rubbings.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will last until April 15.
</P>
<P>
The Yonghe Lamasery, covering a floor space of 66,000 square
meters, now receives more than 1.3 million visitors and followers
of the Buddhist faith each year. It was established in 1694 and
was designated as a place of worship in 1744 for all Tibetan monks
by the then emperor of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
