<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Modernize Intellectual Property Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Attorney-General Amos Wako has
published a draft bill designed to replace the current
intellectual property rights law, as an effort to bring Kenya
into conformity with international instruments.
</P>
<P>
The Bill to be known as the Industrial Property Bill is set to
repeal and replace the existing Industrial Property Act,
according to Thursday's East African Standard newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Wako said Wednesday the bill will replace the statute which
deals with registration and protection of intellectual property
rights in patents, utility models, industrial designs and
rationalization models.
</P>
<P>
The need for amending the current law arose from recent
developments in intellectual property law on the international
scene, including a number of treaties and agreements to which
Kenya is a party, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is a signatory to the Paris Convention for the Protection
of Industrial Property. But a number of provisions of the present
law relating to the expiry of patents, proceedings for their
forfeiture and grant of compulsory licenses are inconsistent with
the Paris Convention, Wako added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
