<HEADLINE> "Atomic Bomb Town" Woos Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Haibei Tibetan Autonomous
Prefecture, where China's first atomic and hydrogen bombs were
born, had attracted investment of over two billion U.S. dollars by
the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture in northwestern Qinghai Province has set up 20
Sino-foreign and solely foreign-funded enterprises and received
300 domestic and overseas businessmen ever since it was
transferred from military control to local government
administration in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the prefecture received foreign investment totaling
250 million dollars. In a bid to woo more funds, efforts have been
made to build roads, power supplies, telecommunications, transport
and other infrastructure facilities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the local government has also tried to develop
Xihaizhen, the seat of the prefectural government and also a
retired nuclear weapons development and production base, into a
tourist scenic spot.
</P>
<P>
After years of development, Xihaizhen has been transformed from
a small barren town into a beautiful garden city.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, it has received nearly 200,000 visitors from home
and abroad.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that an exhibition hall will be built to feature
the construction and development of the town, as well as models of
atomic and hydrogen bombs and biographies of some experts in the
field.  
</P>
</TEXT>
