<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Archeologists Unearth Ancient Tomb Complex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A recent archeological discovery in
the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Regions proves that human beings
lived in Shihezi over 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang Archeologist Zhang Yuzhong said that 13 ancient stone
tombs discovered some 60 km south of the city have yielded many
relics, including 19 pottery articles, nine iron objects and
numerous bone, bronze and agate ornaments.
</P>
<P>
Red pottery articles are decorated with rare triangular, net
and willow leaf patterns, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Remains of individuals were discovered in eleven tombs.
</P>
<P>
The tombs date back over 2,000 years, said Zhang, adding that
iron and bone relics show that ancient nomads led a pastoral life
in the area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
