<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jilin Province Offers Thermotherapy for Tumors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A thermotherapy center for
treating tumors recently opened in northeast China's Jilin
province.
</P>
<P>
A tumor treatment therapy system developed by the center has
passed an expert appraisal.
</P>
<P>
Thermotherapy, a widely recognized "safe treatment" for
malignant tumor, is free of side effects generally associated with
other forms of treatment such as surgery, chemotherapy and
radiotherapy.
</P>
<P>
The treatment involves heating body tissue and maintaining body
temperatures within a specified range in order to kill cancer
cells without harming healthy cells.
</P>
<P>
Clinical tests have achieved noticeable results for 94 percent
of tumor cases after only one or two courses of treatment,
according to researchers at the center.
</P>
<P>
"Thermotherapy not only contains the expansion of tumor cells
in the human body, but also reduces pain and improves both
appetite and sleep, in addition to helping patients regain their
health patients," said Center Director Song Liansheng.
</P>
<P>
Thermotherapy was initiated in the 1960s in a number of
developed countries, including the United States, Japan and some
European nations. China introduced the therapy in 1978.
Thermotherapy is currently offered by a limited number of Chinese
hospitals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Firm to Close Plant in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A Japanese subsidiary company will
shut down its 11-year-old plant here on April 30 as the
Philippines remains helpless in stopping the exodus of
multi-national corporations.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued here Thursday, Uniden
Philippines Inc.'s plant in Manila, the biggest producer of
telecommunication gadgets, will be closed due to "low demand for
its products, aggravated partly by the financial crisis affecting
Asian countries."
</P>
<P>
Uniden will transfer 80 percent of its equipment at the plant
to its affiliate in Laguna, the central Philippines, while the
rest will be shipped to China, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that there is no room for the 2,800
employees to be left by the closure in its Laguna plant, which is
operating at half of its capacity.
</P>
<P>
The laguna plant produces cordless phones with 3,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
Uniden joins a growing list of top multinational corporations
which have decided to relocate their manufacturing operations to
other countries. These corporations include Johnson &AMP; Johnson,
Colgate-Palmolive, Warner Lambert, Philips Lighting and Abbot
Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
They are leaving the Philippines because other countries offer
lower labor cost, better infrastructure and high level of
technological development.
</P>
<P>
Philippine government officials met Uniden officials last week
to convince the Japanese subsidiary company to change its mind.
But Uniden remained firm in its decision because revenues have
fallen behind expenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wizards Stuns Magic 84-73 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Mitch Richmond scored eight of
his 16 points in the fourth quarter Wednesday as the Washington
Wizards held on for an 84-73 victory over the Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
Juwan Howard had 20 points to lead the Wizards, who never
trailed and held Orlando to its second-lowest total this year.
</P>
<P>
Richmond became the 41st player in NBA history to eclipse 18,
000 points with a basket in the opening minute.
</P>
<P>
Nick Anderson, Magic's top scorer, who averages 16.5 points per
game, suffered a left hamstring midway through the second quarter
and did not return without a single point.
</P>
<P>
However, the Magic (22-10), who had won four of their last five
games, still leads the Atlantic Division by one game over Miami (
19-9).
</P>
<P>
In Boston, the Detroit Pistons continued their winning streak
to five games by beating the Celtics 87-72.
</P>
<P>
Lindsey Hunter scored 17 points and Grant Hill added 16 and 11
rebounds for Detroit, which has won seven of its last eight games.
</P>
<P>
Detroit committed just 12 turnovers while forcing 18 Celtics
miscues resulting in 25 points.
</P>
<P>
In Charlotte, Dell Curry, the leading scorer in Hornets'
history, helped the Milwaukee Bucks to their third straight
victory over Hornet 102-94.
</P>
<P>
"It was very satisfying to beat the team that did not want you,
" Curry said. "It was fun tonight. I got the chance to play and
talk a lot."
</P>
<P>
In Phoenix, Tom Gugliotta had 10 of his 21 points in the third
quarter and grabbed 11 rebounds as the Suns romped the Golden
State Warriors 93-78.
</P>
<P>
Gugliotta hit 5-of-6 shots in the third period, including a tip-
in that triggered a 22-6 burst to close the quarter.
</P>
<P>
The Suns entered this contest with two straight home losses and
six in their last eight games at America West Arena while the
Warriors have won just twice in their last 27 games to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
Rookie Antawn Jamison had 16 points and 15 rebounds for Golden
State, which fell 1 1/2 games back of Phoenix for the eighth and
final playoff spot in the Western Conference. The Warriors were
coming off Tuesday's stunning 93-90 win over the league-leading
Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
In Portland, Damon Stoudamire scored 21 points as the Trail
Blazers beat the Chris Webber-absent Sacramento Kings 100-86
though they lost suspended guard Isaiah Rider.
</P>
<P>
Rider was suspended without pay for a league-high third time
this season after entering the stands late in Tuesday night's loss
at Golden State. 
</P>
</TEXT>
