<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Grant $30M to East African States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 1 (Xinhua) -- France will grant some 30
million U.S. dollars for development activities in the three East
African Cooperation (EAC) countries and has also committed one
million U.S. dollars to each of the states for setting up project
preparation funds.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding on this has been signed in the
Arusha town, north Tanzania, where the EAC secretariat is based,
press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony Wednesday, Antoine Pouillieute,
managing director of the French Development Agency (AFD), said 54
million dollars will be injected into the private sector in Kenya,
Tanzania and Uganda, the members of East African Cooperation,
which was founded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Pouillieute expressed France's desire to see vibrant regional
cooperation, assuring that Paris will further strengthen economic
ties with east of African countries.
</P>
<P>
The three countries plan to sign a treaty on July 1 this year
to revive the defunct East African Community which collapsed in
1977 due to divergent economic and political policies.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at establishing a single market and
investment area competitive in the global market, said Francis
Muthaura, executive secretary of the Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between EAC and AFD will focus on the development
of economic infrastructures, including cooperation in development
of telecommunications, energy, water resources, rail, roads and
civil aviation, Lake Victoria, rural and pastoral areas, national
parks and border towns, tourism, natural resources and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
AFD was established in 1941 as the key executing agency of
French overseas development assistance. In 1997, the agency
extended its operations in east Africa by opening a regional
representative office in Nairobi responsible for development
projects in Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Burundi and Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
