<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: "Stop the Bombing, Stop the War" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
His paper-turned placard reads "NATO: Stop Your Aggression!" It
looks just like a small tree in the colorful forest of placards,
which bear varying slogans denouncing the NATO air strikes against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 Yugoslav people took to the street in Manhattan,
downtown area of the New York City, to protest against the U.S.-
led NATO attacks on Yugoslavia, a sovereign and independent member
of the U.N. family.
</P>
<P>
Two Serb girls painted their faces, arms and shirts in red,
imitating the image of bloodshed in the wake of the NATO attacks
in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Clad in a black robe, Rev. Demetrios Cantos, Greek Orthodox
Archdiocese of America, told Xinhua, "It's terrible for NATO to
bomb my country, the United States must stop the bombing and
return to peaceful negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Wearing the image of a shooting target on the back, protesters
intend to tell the U.S.-led NATO, "Come, and bomb us, we are not
afraid!"
</P>
<P>
"The people of Yugoslavia are not going to be defeated by the
bombing, the people of Yugoslavia are all behind the government in
Belgrade more than ever they have before," said Barry Lituchy, one
of the organizers of the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
The Wednesday demonstration, called by the International Action
Center, followed a huge March 27 protest that drew 7,000 people
who marched through Manhattan chanting "Stop the bombing, stop the
war" and "Kosovo is Vietnam."
</P>
<P>
On March 27, there were also demonstrations of 2,000 in Los
Angeles, San Francisco and Washington D.C. Earlier, protesters
also took to the street in Sacramento, Boston, Chicago, Columbus,
Teledo, Seattle, Madison and other cities across the United States.
</P>
<P>
NATO, without the authorization of the U.N. Security Council,
started air strikes against Yugoslavia on March 24, a move seen as
a flagrant violation of the U.N. Charter and international law.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators also accused U.S. media, such as the New York
Times, one of widely-circulated newspapers in America, of lying in
the coverage of the conflict of Kosovo, a Serbian province in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts broke out in February last year after ethnic
Albanians, who make up some 90 percent of the province's
population of 2 million, have been fighting with Serbs for
independence.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill "Clinton portrays this bombing as a
humanitarian gesture on behalf of the Albanian national minority
that resides in Kosovo, a region of Yugoslavia. That is a lie,"
said Lituchy, who has been teaching Modern European History for
almost 10 years at the City University of New York.
</P>
<P>
"It is war propaganda designed to justify and conceal the real
objective of this war of aggression," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The real U.S./NATO goal is to break up Yugoslavia into ever-
smaller pieces and bomb its people into submission," Petrovich
said, "The Balkans is a key strategic region, a crossroads between
Western Europe and the oil-rich Middle East and Caspian basin."
</P>
<P>
"We are here to tell the American people that the war is not
justifiable and the U.S. government is wasting their money to
create bloodshed in our country," Lituchy said.
</P>
<P>
As the Yugoslav people demonstrated in New York, NATO was
intensifying its air assault on Yugoslavia, pounding targets on
Wednesday near a major Kosovo city. Eight people, including
civilians, were killed on the same day by NATO bombing in Belgrade
area.
</P>
<P>
"We are planning to demonstrate every week until the bombing
ends," Lituchy said. "Serbian people have a long history of
fighting foreign aggression, fighting colonialism, fighting
imperialism, and they are not going to back down." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
