<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Privatize 51 State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
privatize 51 state-owned enterprises (SOEs) in 1999, a report in
The Independent daily newspaper said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at an inter-ministerial meeting early
this month, which also decided to sell the state's shares in 19
other enterprises this year.
</P>
<P>
Of the 51 enterprises, nine are under the Bangladesh Textile
Mills Corporation, seven under the Bangladesh Jute Mills
Corporation, five under the Bangladesh Sugar and Food Industries
Corporation, six under the Bangladesh Steel and Engineering
Corporation and four under the Bangladesh Chemical Industries
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Kazi Zafrullah, chairman of the Privatization Board, proposed
names of 60 enterprises for privatization, but the meeting
finalized a list of only 51 enterprises for transfer to the
private sector, the report said. The board was set up in 1993 to
privatize the loss-making SOEs.
</P>
<P>
There are about 300 SOEs in the country, with the total value
of output accounting for about 6 percent of the gross domestic
product and incurring a loss of about 568 million U.S. dollars
every year.
</P>
<P>
The Privatization Board has handed over a total of 17 SOEs to
private entrepreneurs since 1993, with 12 of them up to 1996 and
five in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The board, which issued letters of intent for handing over five
projects in 1997 and four enterprises in 1998, failed to hand over
any SOEs last year though 87 enterprises were enlisted, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Zafrullah as saying on Wednesday that the
process of privatization of the SOEs was "very lengthy and
complicated" and that the performance of the board should be
judged on the basis of the number of enterprises privatized.
</P>
<P>
He said the board has succeeded in creating public opinion in
favor of privatization and has established good relations with
labor in respect of privatization.
</P>
<P>
New laws to expedite privatization in the country are to come
into force soon and new legislation would facilitate foreign
investors to buy the SOEs, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
