<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices of Hides, Skin Low in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The prices of hides and skin in
Bangladesh after the Eid-ul-Azha, one of the country's major
religious festivals which falls on late March, are lower this year
than last year.
</P>
<P>
Trading at Postagola in the old part of the capital city, the
country's largest wholesale market for raw leather, was "dull"
this year, because of a smaller number of buyers, a tight loan
disbursement policy of banks and lower demand for finished leather
in the international market, The Daily Star newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The price of an average size of cow hide is 600 to 800 taka
(about 12.5-16.7 U.S. dollars) this year against 800 to 1,000 taka
(about 16.7-20.8 dollars) last year, and the average price of a
goat skin is 110 to 135 taka (about 2.3-2.8 dollars) against last
year's 125 to 150 taka (about 2.6-3.1 dollars), Alhaj Azizur
Rahman, president of the Bangladesh Hides and Skin Merchants
Association, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the prices declined as most of the tanneries are
not buying leather due to less cash flow and a ban on export of
wet blue leather.
</P>
<P>
They added that if the prices go down further, huge quantities
of raw leather would be smuggled to India, where traders would buy
raw leather at higher prices and could export half-processed wet
blue leather.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 percent of the total procurement of leather in the
country is made during the Eid festival.
</P>
<P>
Rahman said the market would pick up if the government withdrew
the ban on export of wet blue leather and banks increased loans to
tanners and leather traders. The four nationalized commercial
banks disbursed around 1.75 billion-taka (about 36.46 million
dollars) in loans this year for procurement of leather, against
last year's 2.5 billion taka (about 52.08 million dollars), he
said.
</P>
<P>
Out of 170 godown owners at Postagola, only around 30 have
started buying leather. "The rest are inactive due to crisis of
fund," he said.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the leather industry, an important
foreign exchange earner of Bangladesh, earned 160 billion taka
(3.3 billion dollars) in foreign exchange from 1972-1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
