<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, April 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- New orders to the U.S. factories fell sharply in
February as demand for costly transportation goods like new
commercial aircraft contracted significantly, the Commerce
Department said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Total factory orders were down 2.5 percent to 340.5 billion U.S.
dollars, the biggest monthly falloff since a 2.6 percent plunge in
April 1995, following a revised 1.5 percent January increase. (U.
S.-Orders)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The Dow Jones industrial average fell again in the
second day after closing above 10,000 as traders continued to get
worried about the company earnings and take profits.
</P>
<P>
The Dow finished down 127.10 at 9,786.16, retreating from an 88.
80 gain in the first hour of trading. The index lost 220.62 points
in the past two days after it crossed the five digit milestone,
finishing at 10,006.78 for the first time Monday. (US-Wall Street-
Closing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- An Asian economic recovery, which is under way in
several of the key regional economies, will gain momentum later
this year, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) said in a latest
report received here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that virtually all countries in the area will
show positive growth next year. (Thailand-Asian Economies)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South Africa's Production Price Index (PPI)
showed an annual rate of increase of five percent in February, the
highest since September 1997, when it was 6.1 percent, Statistics
South Africa announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This rate is 0.6 percentage points higher than the
corresponding rate of 4.4 percent in January. (SAfrica-Producer
Inflation) 
</P>
</TEXT>
