<HEADLINE> DPRK Demands U.S. Compensation for Halting Missile Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) is demanding compensation from the United
States for lost earnings if it halts its missile exports, said a
spokesman for the DPRK Foreign Ministry on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the fourth round of missile talks in Pyongyang on Monday
and Tuesday, the DPRK insisted that only after Washington accepted
this condition could the two sides discuss the halt of missile
exports, the spokesman told the Korean Central News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the DPRK was only willing to negotiate
on the issue of missile exports, but not activities involving the
development of missiles.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK insisted during the talks that "the development,
production, test and deployment of missiles fall completely within
the category of our sovereignty and we will never enter into
negotiations with anybody over such activities," the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two sides discussed the proposal put
forward by the DPRK and decided to continue the negotiations in
future, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The date and venue for the next round of talks will be fixed
and chosen through the contact channel in New York, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denounced for NATO Airstrikes on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A noted Finnish expert on
international issues said that the ongoing NATO airstrikes on
Yugoslavia have brought to light once again the U.S. attempt to
seek hegemony in the post-Cold War world.
</P>
<P>
Carl Fredrik Sandelin said in a commentary which was published
in the Wednesday issue of Hufvudstadsbladet (Capital Daily) that U.
S. President Bill Clinton and NATO are waging a war of aggression
on Yugoslavia, an independent and sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
NATO military action is totally unacceptable as Yugoslavia has
never attacked the United States or NATO, nor has it posed a
threat to them, said Sandelin, who was former president of the
Finnish News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He criticized NATO for launching military strikes on Yugoslavia
without the authorization of the United Nations, describing the
airstrikes as a flagrant intervention in Yugoslavia's internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Some European countries yielded to the U.S. hegemonic moves to
take part in the aggression of Yugoslavia even though they are
clearly aware that military strikes can not bring a solution to
the Kosovo issue, Sandelin said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Kosovo issue should be solved through
diplomatic channels instead of force, adding the United States,
the only superpower in the current world, has become used to
applying to arms to carry out its foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
Sandelin warned Europe's NATO countries not to let Washington,
who calls the current war of aggression on Yugoslavia a
humanitarian mission to protect ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, make a
new mistake in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
He said that NATO airstrikes in the past few days failed to
force the Yugoslav government and people to back down, but would
rather cause more casualties to innocent civilians. 
</P>
