<HEADLINE> Pentagon: Three U.S. Army Soldiers Missing in Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Three U.S. Army soldiers on a
reconnaissance mission on the Macedonian-Yugoslav border were
missing Wednesday night after being surrounded and fired upon, the
U.S. Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
An immediate search and rescue mission was launched, involving
ground and helicopter teams, Defense Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
The three-man reconnaissance team had been traveling in the
Kumanovo area of Macedonia near the southern Yugoslavia border
when they reported they received small arms fire and said they
were surrounded, the Pentagon quoted a NATO statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The statement didn't say who had them surrounded. Pentagon
spokesman Richard Bridges said, "We believe they have possibly
been abducted. Right now, there's a search and rescue effort on."
</P>
<P>
At the White House, National Security Adviser Sandy Berger
advised President Clinton of the missing "and will keep him
informed as the information becomes available," said National
Security Council spokesman David Leavy.
</P>
<P>
"We're still determined to push forward on our sustained air
campaign and the operation will continue" against military targets
in Yugoslavia, Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
Leavy declined to provide further details "that could
potentially jeopardize the safety or well being of these guys."
</P>
<P>
NATO forces, including ground and helicopter teams, and
Macedonian police immediately launched an immediate search for the
missing team, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Army reconnaissance team was part of the former U.N.
peacekeeping operation in Macedonia called "Able Sentry," which
ended in February, Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
The force of about 1,200 troops included about 350 Americans,
who remained in the region following the March 24 start of NATO
airstrikes on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
