<HEADLINE> Jilin Province Targets Illegal Publications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Jilin Province
has effectively checked the resurgence of illegal publications.
</P>
<P>
The concrete move to fight subversive, pornographic and pirate
publications has included spot-checks of more than 2,000
bookstores and outlets of electronic publications since early this
year.
</P>
<P>
Authorities have confiscated over 86,000 illegal books and
magazines, as well as 235,000 electronic publications, including
more than 10,000 pornographic CDs. Related efforts have led to the
closure of 12 printing houses suspected to producing illegal
publications and 49 outlets operating without permits.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities also confiscated more than 5,000 pirated CDs
and some 500 illegal books and magazines sold in rural cultural
markets, in addition to closing dozens of illegal outlets.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to restructure some 3,000 printing houses
during April in order to halt the production of pornographic and
pirated publications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
