<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Gets 1 Bln Dollars in Customs Duties in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar gained a total of 1.135
billion U.S. dollars in customs duties in 1998, according to the
latest data published by the country's Central Statistical
Organization.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total, import duties amounted to 1.118 billion
dollars, including 810 million dollars through normal trade and
308 million dollars through border trade.
</P>
<P>
The duties collected on export commodities accounted for 17
million dollars only.
</P>
<P>
The figures also indicate that the total customs duties income
was 1.274 billion dollars in 1997, 139 million dollars more than
that in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Myanmar made some adjustment in the rate of
customs duties in an effort to boost the development of
agriculture. The country exempted import duties on agricultural
implements including related machinery, pesticide and fertilizer
while raising the import duties of luxury goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
