<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Speed Up Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Senior Thai government officials
said various ministries have received orders from Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai to speed up public spending in the 1999 fiscal year
in a bid to stimulate domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
"The premier wants us to speed up government spending as only
30 percent of the budget has been disbursed as of March 20,"
Supachai Pisitvanich, the Finance Ministry's permanent secretary,
said in remarks made public on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan issued the order after the cabinet on March 30 approved
a 130-billion-baht (3.5 billion U.S. dollars) stimulus package to
kick-start economic recovery by increasing domestic demand and
spending.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister convened a meeting of permanent secretaries
from all ministries on Wednesday to ensure that the package will
render good results. There have been reports about expected delays
in disbursement of the national budget as well as offshore loans.
</P>
<P>
In the fiscal year, starting October 1, 1998, to September 31,
1999, the government hopes that it would be able to disburse up to
89 percent of the total budget of 825 billion baht (22.2 billion
dollars). So far, the spending is at a slow pace.
</P>
<P>
So far, disbursement delays are being partly given as a reason
for the prolonged economic recession. But Supachai insisted that
the delays are mainly because of contractors' financial problems,
which have made them unable to complete projects as planned.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said 53 billion baht (1.4 billion dollars) out of the
130-billion-baht package would soon be disbursed to rural
projects.
</P>
<P>
He said offshore loans will be disbursed faster due to the
small size of projects and the shortening of bureaucratic
procedures.
</P>
<P>
Rural officials will be in charge of spending, without having
to wait for the central government's decision. The Interior
Ministry will give each village 100,000 baht (2,700 dollars) for
job creation.
</P>
<P>
To speed up disbursement, every ministry has 15 days to submit
all details of projects to the Budget Bureau. The bureau will take
only 10 days in examining the projects and the
Comptroller-General's Department will dispatch the funds within a
day if asked, according to Satit Limpongphun, the Finance
Ministry's spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
