<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Lawmakers Strongly Condemn NATO Action in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Federation Council (
upper house of the parliament) issued a statement Wednesday,
strongly condemning NATO's air attacks against Yugoslavia as an
aggressive act.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the lawmakers expressed support to the
efforts by President Boris Yeltsin and the government to
immediately stop the bombings and settle the crisis as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
The document stressed that the purpose of NATO's air raids
against Yugoslavia, which has lasted for eight days by Wednesday,
is to impose its own will on a sovereign nation and to set up in
the 21st century a unipolar world ruled by Washington.
</P>
<P>
The behavior of NATO undermines the reputation of the United
Nations, noted the Federation Council, which first appealed to the
international community to stop NATO invasion last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Those who have hatched and carried out the aggression should be
held responsible for its consequences, and the legislators of NATO
member nations who authorized it should also be blamed, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It suggested that Russian president and the government call for
an urgent meeting of the UN Security Council to discuss the issues
of NATO's violation of the UN Charter and of lifting the U.N.-
imposed sanctions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
It also proposed that the Russian government discuss the issue
of providing for the invaded country necessary economic aid as
well as military technology that could be used for defensive
purpose.
</P>
<P>
The statement appealed to such organizations as the
Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE),
European Union, Inter-parliamentary Union and Black Sea Economic
Cooperation Organization to act to halt immediately NATO's
aggression, and to bring the Kosovo crisis back to the track of
political settlement.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers also called on their counterparts of the
Commonwealth of Independent States to stand by Russia's stance of
peacefully resolving the crisis in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the current gloomy political and military situation
in Europe, the council proposed to re-examine the basic
principles of the security concept concerning the CIS countries,
and to take steps to strengthen their national defense in a quick
manner.
</P>
<P>
The council backed the CIS countries to give humanitarian aid
to the Yugoslav people and at the same time to establish a fund
for the victims of the invasion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
