<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Forecasts Quick Recovery in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 1 (Xinhua) -- An Asian economic recovery, which
is under way in several of the key regional economies, will gain
momentum later this year, the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
said in a latest report received here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that virtually all countries in the area will
show positive growth next year.
</P>
<P>
The IMF forecast shows that Thailand and South Korea will
record 1-percent and 2-percent overall economic growth
respectively while China's economy will continue to grow 7 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
However, Japan, Indonesia, Malaysia and Hong Kong are forecast
to remain in negative growth territory in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The IMF figures show that Japan's GDP will contract 1.1 percent
this year, after a 1998 contraction of 2.8 percent. Japan is
forecast to grow 0.3 percent in 2000. Indonesia, meanwhile, will
see a contraction of 3.9 percent in 1999 after a 1998 reduction of
13.6 percent. Indonesia's economy is forecast to grow 3.3 percent
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to the IMF, Malaysia will see a GDP contraction of
1.6 percent in 1999 after a 1998 reduction of 7.5 percent. It is
forecast to record growth of 1.1 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
While the IMF did not specifically mention the export recovery
of Asian economies, the 1999 outlook is unclear for Thailand as
well as other Asian countries. However, the outlook for solid
export recovery is clearer in 2000, according to Thai government
officials.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's export recovery, targeted to grow 4 percent this
year in dollar terms but with actual shipments in January and
February down 5.6 percent, is one of the twin engines of growth
along with the recovery of domestic demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
