<HEADLINE> 11 Armed Group Members Surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 11 members of various
anti-government armed groups surrendered to the Myanmar government
in February, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
These armed group members included those from the ethnic Kayin
National Union (KNU) and Arakan Independence Army (AIA).
</P>
<P>
They laid down their arms in different military command areas
including the Coastal Region.
</P>
<P>
In armed opposition to the Myanmar government, the KNU and the
AIA reportedly operate in the Myanmar-Thai and Myanmar-Bangladesh
border areas respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, more than 500 members from
various anti-government armed groups "exchanged arms for peace"
with the government last year.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 17 anti-government ethnic armed groups as well as
the former drug trafficking Mong Tai Army (MTA) have made peace
with the government. 
</P>
