<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial System Reform To Move Into New Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- China's financial system reform
needs to be raised to the next stage, said Chinese economist Zhao
Haikuan in today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
First, the People's Bank of China should be turned into a more
standard central bank, Zhao said in a signed article.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, quota management of credit was removed and the
People's Bank of China turned to economic methods instead of a
mandatory plan for macro-economic control.
</P>
<P>
It reformed its institutional structure, abolished its branches
at provincial and municipal levels and established transprovincial
branches in nine major regions, including Shanghai and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
It is therefore faced with creating new work rules to fully
bring into play the advantages of the new structure and to
strengthen financial supervision.
</P>
<P>
Second, conditions should be created to implement a
shareholding system in State-owned banks, said the article.
</P>
<P>
Despite various measures taken by the State, including closer
control of assets-to-liabilities ratios, reform of State-owned
banks still lags far behind the set goals.
</P>
<P>
Form time to time, major State-owned banks are still required
to grant loans based on public policy criteria.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans, a problem worsening over time, have not
been effectively resolved.
</P>
<P>
A shareholding system would push the wheel of reform forward,
said the article.
</P>
<P>
It would facilitate the separation of government and commercial
activity in the whole banking sector.
</P>
<P>
With such a mechanism, banks will belong to the shareholders.
Although the State may become the biggest shareholder and control
the direction of a bank's development, it cannot maintain complete
control.
</P>
<P>
Shareholders will use every possible means to force banks to
improve their management and pursue maximum profits.
</P>
<P>
As a result, credit channels will be boosted and non-performing
loans can be partly alleviated.
</P>
<P>
China's financial market should be further opened and
standardized, said the article.
</P>
<P>
Renminbi in capital accounts should be made freely convertible
when conditions are ripe.
</P>
<P>
Conditions include the further expansion of China's economic
strength and the emergence of capable bankers who are skilled in
international financial business operations and proficient in
handling international financial strategies.
</P>
<P>
The Renminbi could then become one of the most important
currencies in the world, said the article. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
