<HEADLINE> Russia to Send Warships to Mediterranean in Response to NATO Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Russia will send seven warships to
the Mediterranean in the nearest days in response to NATO
airstrikes against Yugoslavia, said Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that the first warship, one military
reconnaissance vessel of the Black Sea Fleet, will leave Friday "
to sail through the Bosporus to monitor NATO actions to enhance
Russia's security."
</P>
<P>
Russia had sent the Turkish government an application for their
transit permission, he said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's foreign ministry Wednesday granted permission to the
Russian warships to transit through the Bosporus strait. Ankara
informed NATO of its decision.
</P>
<P>
Russia has said repeatedly that its military will not become
involved in the conflict in Yugoslavia. Sergeyev's statement came
amidst Russian press reports that a squadron of seven ships,
including missile frigates and anti-submarine frigates from the
Black Sea Fleet, will be sent to the Mediterranean in early April.
</P>
<P>
The appearance of a Russian naval squadron in the Mediterranean
would cause concern among NATO commanders. U.S. and allied
warships are deployed in the region for operations against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov returned to Moscow Wednesday
after his diplomatic mission to Yugoslavia failed to produce a
breakthrough. He said Moscow would continue efforts to revive
talks on ending the Kosovo dispute.
</P>
<P>
The Russian military has suspended contacts with NATO in
protest over the alliance's action in Yugoslavia, and recalled its
general who represents the Defense Ministry at NATO headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
