<HEADLINE> China Formulates Child Welfare Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- China is mapping out a new
development program for the well-being of its children as the
nation prepares to enter the new millennium, today's "China Daily"
reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quotes Li Qimin, an
official of the National Working Committee for Children and Women
as saying that the new program will promotes child-related
development projects focusing on health care, elementary education
and nutrition.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that despite a national average
immunization rate over 95 percent, the rate in some remote and
impoverished regions still hovers around 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
The new ten-year program will be drafted by a number of
departments, including the ministries of health, education, and
labor, co-ordinated by Li's office.
</P>
<P>
China's current program for children's development, adopted in
1992, is a China-oriented version based on the guidelines set by a
summit on the issue of international children in 1990.
</P>
<P>
According to a November report, China had reached 14 of the 24
global standards set by the conference, including providing safe
drinking water in rural regions, reducing the death rate of
infants and children under five by one-third, and promoting
breastfeeding.
</P>
<P>
Six targets, such as the building of hygienic public toilets in
rural areas, the elimination of iodine deficiency disease, and the
control of AIDS, are not likely to be met by the end of the
century.
</P>
<P>
Some 78 percent of China's 340 million children live in rural
areas, where economic development is relatively slow and health
knowledge is not wide-spread. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
