<HEADLINE> Beijing to Reduce Transient Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing municipal government
has vowed to slash the size of the city's transient population,
China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
This applies to all those Chinese who work in Beijing but who
do not have a residence certificate, a municipal official was
quoted by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Quanfu, Beijing now has 2.859 million residents
from other parts of China who do not have residence certificates
and 1.8 million of them are working in the city.
</P>
<P>
"And the number is still increasing, which exceeds our needs
and imposes too great a burden on the city's infrastructure and
services," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to reduce the number from 1.8 million to 1.
5 million, Li said.
</P>
<P>
To fulfill the goal, Beijing will expand its 5,000-strong
Special Administrative Team by another 7,000 to supervise the
transient population, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, since these people mainly live in leased housing,
Beijing will further strengthen supervision of such housing this
year.
</P>
<P>
New measures in this field include establishing files for all
of Beijing's leased housing and closing all illegally leased
housing in the city before June, it reported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
