<HEADLINE> Sydney Plans to Random Test Olympic Athletes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The world's athletes are likely
to have random drug tests in the two weeks before the 2000 Games,
as Sydney Olympic organizers announced (SOCOG) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sydney Organizing Committee sports commission chairman John
Coates said the two-week period prior to a major event is crucial
for supervising drugs cheats.
</P>
<P>
The organizers want to test athletes staying in the Athletes
Village and at training camps in Australia.
</P>
<P>
Coates said he hoped the new International Anti-Doping Agency
would provide the funding for the out-of-competition testing if
agreement could be reached with the international sporting
federations and national Olympic committees.
</P>
<P>
Under current rules, athletes are the responsibility of their
sports' federations until the start of an Olympics when the IOC
takes over.
</P>
<P>
SOCOG plans to drug-test 2,200 athletes during the Games.
</P>
<P>
Coates said he was hopeful that reliable tests would be found
for human growth hormone and the red blood cell stimulant EPO
before the Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
