<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Asia Facing Deflation Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Asia is facing the threat of
deflation, which, economists suggest, would harm the region's
economy and slow down the pace of a recovery if it fails to get
out of the mess.
</P>
<P>
What is deflation? It is a decrease in the amount of money
being used in a country that leads to weak demand for goods, less
industrial activities and lower prices. That is the explanation of
experts.
</P>
<P>
To consumers, however, falling prices for goods and services
mean more purchasing power although they also suggest slack
demand, over-supply and lower income and high unemployment. All
these problems could harm the economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The deflation trend in Asian began from mid-1997 to mid-1998
when some East Asian currencies devalued by 30 to 80 percent. The
crushing devaluations helped lower the dollar prices of many Asian
exports.
</P>
<P>
Some people said the International Monetary Fund's original
cure of compelling governments to produce austerity budgets should
take some of the blame.
</P>
<P>
Signs of deflation have started to appear in Asia during the
last two years: Real estate prices across Asia have been depressed
and market capitalization on the region's bourses has been
slashed, by 40 percent in Seoul, 63 percent in Bangkok and 81
percent in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, consumer prices, from housing to food, telephone
services to television sets, have been falling in many Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, consumer prices have been retreating since last
June while in Japan, prices have been falling for about six years.
</P>
<P>
In some Asian countries, consumers almost have stopped buying
to wait for further price drops while companies are laying off
more workers because they can not sell their goods.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, unemployed workers have little spending power and are
making the downward spiral take another turn. In Japan, February's
unemployment rate climbed to 4.6 percent, a record high, while
retail sales were down 3.5 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that as prices drop in an industry facing glut,
companies may have to cut capacity and work force to stay
competitive, and in some sectors, firms will have to close.
</P>
<P>
As the inflation rate in many Asian countries has become almost
negative and over-supply of goods further lowered prices,
deflation could prolong Asia's economic recovery process, they
warned.
</P>
<P>
To combat the threat of deflation, Asian countries have
initiated big spending programs to prevent the economic recovery
process from derailing.
</P>
<P>
Many Asian governments have increased public spending to
stimulate the economic growth and avoid deflation. Since the
second half of 1998, East Asian countries have abandoned the
International Monetary Fund's austerity programs and increased
budget deficits by spending more on infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Most Asian countries have also cut interest rates to push
consumption demand higher and stimulate production. In the
Philippines, the central bank has lowered its key interest rates
seven times to 12.5 percent so far this year, close to the
pre-crisis level.
</P>
<P>
But some experts said that under the pressure of falling prices
and over-supply, the best way to cure deflation is to abandon
old-fashioned technologies and unprofitable factories.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, in Asia, only Japan has displayed signs of serious
deflation. Japanese consumers have begun to factor an expectation
of falling prices into buying decisions.
</P>
<P>
However, economists said Asian governments should recognize the
seriousness of the deflation threat and adopt more measures to
prevent deflation from occurring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Tap Tourism Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- China's tourism industry should be
considered a new, large-potential economic growth sector, suggests
a senior tourism official.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the industry can tap into China's vast
countryside, and underdeveloped central and western regions, notes
Wei Xiao'an, director of the Policy and Regulation Department of
China National Tourism Administration (CNTA).
</P>
<P>
Villages, China's main support base for sustainable development,
have natural, tourism-based resources, Wei was quoted by China
Daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
With improvements in people's living standards, more urban
citizens prefer visiting villages because they have fresher air
and cleaner water, said Wei.
</P>
<P>
Most rural areas are more accessible due to improved
transportation conditions in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
For example, each prefecture in Yunnan Province has a modern
airport , and the province earned 264 million US dollars in
tourism revenues in 1997, up from 13 million US dollars in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Other provinces have applied to establish local ecological
tourism development zones, such as Hulunbeier grasslands in Inner
Mongolia and Linzhi Guogao Lake Resort.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of travelers to China's population jumped from
23.7 percent in 1990 to 52.4 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"As a pillar industry in most provinces, tourism can play an
important role in increasing investments, expanding demands and
enlarging exports," Wei said.
</P>
<P>
The number of domestic tourists grew 10 percent annually during
the past 14 years, indicate official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Some 694 million people traveled throughout China last year.
</P>
<P>
The domestic tourism sector reported 239.1 billion yuan in
earnings last year, despite the severe flooding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
