<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: Xiandu and IYVWC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ZHEJIANG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The '99 China International Young
Volunteers Work Camp on Environment Protection and Culture
Exchange opened at Xiandu in east China's Zhejiang province today.
</P>
<P>
Xiandu, one of China's major scenic spots, is situated in
Jinyun County in Zhejiang Province, and has more than 300 places
of interest including Dinghu Peak, Niweng Cave, Red Cliff, and the
Mother and Daughter-in-Law Rocks.
</P>
<P>
With 160 spectacular peaks and 27 marvelous caves, Xiandu
compares with beautiful Guilin, splendid Huangshan, and
precipitous Huashan which are well-known in China.
</P>
<P>
Dinghu Peak is at the center of interest; shaped like a bamboo
shoot in spring, it rises 170 meters into the sky, covers a ground
area of 2,468 square meters and a top area of 710 square meters,
and is known as "The First Highest Peak on Earth."
</P>
<P>
An old legend said that Emperor Huangdi had pills of
immortality made there, then died and went to heaven.
</P>
<P>
Xiandu is a place of abundant greenery and clean, clear air.
Far from the city, it is an ideal spot for young people to develop
a sense of environmental protection and persistence.
</P>
<P>
More than ten international volunteers from countries
including Britain, the Netherlands, Singapore and Japan will
gather there to attend The '99 China International Young
Volunteers Work Camp.
</P>
<P>
The idea of work camps was established in 1920 by the youth of
Germany and France to reconstruct the buildings destroyed in their
countries during World War I.
</P>
<P>
The work camp, a kind of volunteer service for youth,
generally lasts two to three weeks, and participants take part in
activities of environmental protection, public service, and
cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The volunteers pay for their own registration and
transportation, but board and lodging are provided free.
</P>
<P>
This will be the third time the All-China Youth Federation (
ACYF) conducts this event in China, since it attended the meeting
of the Coordinating Committee for International Voluntary Service
(CCIVS) in 1997 for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The CCIVS includes 68 member states and organizes 1,600 work
camps annually worldwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Starts Population, Housing Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- About 250,000 census enumerators and
supervisors have started visiting all households throughout the
country Thursday morning to investigate Vietnam's population and
housing conditions at 0 hour of April 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
This is Vietnam's third nationwide population census after the
country's reunification.
</P>
<P>
Le Van Toan, head of Vietnam's Central Steering Committee for
the Census, recently said at a press conference here, "This is a
large and important census aimed at collecting information to
reflect the current status of population and housing condition for
the country as a whole and its local areas, responding information
need to formulate socioeconomic development plans in the period
from 2000 to 2010."
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese population and housing census, which will
conclude on April 7, is to collect information on population by
sex, age, ethnic group, religion, urban and rural areas; levels
and trends of migration; education and qualification; Labor force
and employment; marital status: fertility, mortality and
population growth; current status of housing conditions; some
facilities of family households and main production means.
</P>
<P>
The initial results of the census will be made public in June
1999, and full results, at the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam conducted its first nationwide census on October 1,
1979, and second on April 1, 1989.
</P>
<P>
According to an official of Vietnam's General Statistical
Bureau, Vietnamese population is nearly 80 million at present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
