<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czechs Keeps Winning Streak in Euro 2000 Qualifiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic was the only
country that has won five straight games for a perfect record in
its hunt for a European title after its runner-up finish to
Germany in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Czechs won their fifth straight by beating Scotland 2-1 on
Wednesday in one of 16 European 2000 Championship qualifiers
across the continent.
</P>
<P>
Germany, Latvia and Spain, with a hat trick by Raul Gonzalez to
give him seven goals in the last two games, overtook the lead in
their groups, while powerful Ukraine stayed on top despite a 1-1
draw with Iceland.
</P>
<P>
World Cup champion France struggled to a 2-0 win over Armenia,
while Italy, Group 1 leaders, was held to a 1-1 draw by lowly
Belarus, the first draw for the Italians after three victories.
</P>
<P>
Group 1:
</P>
<P>
In Ancona, Italy drew 1-1 with Belarus for 10 points from four
matches. Valentin Belkevich gave Belarus an early lead in the 24th,
but was equalised by Italy with a penalty kick six minutes later
after midfielder Antonio Conte was fouled. Belarus has two draws
in four games.
</P>
<P>
Stephane Chapuisat scored twice to propel Switzerland to a 2-0
victory in Zurich over Wales, boosting its hopes of reaching the
finals, at least as a runner-up as the Swiss have seven points
against six for Wales.
</P>
<P>
Group 2:
</P>
<P>
A scoreless draw between Greece and Latvia enabled the latter
to overtake Norway on goal difference as group leader as Latvia,
which began playing internationally only eight years ago, upset
Norway earlier 3-1.
</P>
<P>
Group 3:
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Germany scored two goals through Jens
Jeremies in the 31st and Oliver Neuville in the 36th to beat
Finland 2-0 to take the group lead on goal difference from Turkey.
Finland has never beaten Germany in 76 years in a full
international.
</P>
<P>
In its away game, Northern Ireland drew 0-0 with Moldova in a
lackluster match. Moldova has only two points in five games and
Northern Ireland has five in as many games.
</P>
<P>
Group 4:
</P>
<P>
Ukraine was also cornered for a disappointing 1-1 draw with
Iceland but still held onto the group leadership on goal
difference over France. Ukraine's Vladyslav Vaschuk got his side a
1-0 lead in the 57th, but Iceland equalized in the 66th on Larus
Sigurdsson's goal. Iceland has nine points in five games and
Ukraine and France has 11 in five.
</P>
<P>
World Cup champion France lacked firepower as it struggled to
beat lowly Armenia 2-0 on first-half goals by Sylvain Wiltord and
Christophe Dugarry, while Russia got its second victory
dispatching Andorra 6-1 as striker Vladimir Beschastnykh scored
twice.
</P>
<P>
Group 5:
</P>
<P>
Sweden won its away game over Poland 1-0 on Fredrik Ljungberg's
goal in the 36th, to strenching its winning streak to four, and
Bulgaria still kept its slim hopes as it beat Luxembourg 2-0
through captain Hristo Stoichkov in the 17th and Ivailo Iordanov
in the 37th.
</P>
<P>
Group 6:
</P>
<P>
Spain whitewashed San Marino 6-0 as Raul Gonzalez made his hat
trick for seven goals in the last two games, overtaking Cyprus for
the group top position on goal difference. Gonzalez scored four
goals in a weekend 9-0 win over Austria.
</P>
<P>
Group 7:
</P>
<P>
Romanian won a hard away game against Azerbaijan through a
lonely goal from Florentin Petre in the 49th, thus scored 11
points from five games, while Slovakia failed to exploit its home
advantage to settle for a scoreless draw with Hungary.
</P>
<P>
As no games played in Group 8 due to war in Kosova, Portugal
kept the Group 9 lead with a 5-0 victory over winless
Liechtenstein. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
