<HEADLINE> Russian State Duma Delegation Leaves for Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of the Russian State
Duma (lower house) left here Wednesday night for Belgrade to visit
Yugoslavia under NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
The visit is a continuation of the Russian government's efforts
to peacefully solve the Balkan crisis, said Sergei Baburin, Duma
deputy speaker and delegation head, before leaving.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, made up of members of all main political
parties in the Duma, will make every effort to stop NATO air
strikes, said Baburin.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, it will meet Yugoslav leaders and tour the
bombed areas and the civilians.
</P>
<P>
As NATO air strikes have shut air passage over Yugoslavia, the
delegation had to fly to Hungary first, and then drive to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov held talks
with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, Milosevic agreed to reduce the Yugoslav forces in
Kosovo and let refugees return homes in exchange for a halt to
NATO offensive, which was rejected by NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
