<HEADLINE> Missile Falls Near Bulgarian Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A missile fell early Wednesday
morning near the village of Elovdol of Per Nik Region in western
Bulgaria close to the border with Yugoslavia, the press office of
the Interior Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The missile was found 500 meters from the village, which is
some 20 kilometers away from the border with Yugoslavia, and has
caused a hole in the ground measuring 6 meter in diameter, the
press office said.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary data, it was a missile similar to the
one which fell near the western Bulgarian city of Trun on March 26.
The warhead exploded in the air, causing no damage.
</P>
<P>
After the March 26 incident, the Bulgarian Foreign Ministry
contacted the U.S. charge d'affaires ad interim to Bulgaria to
express uneasiness over the matter. The U.S. diplomat promised to
report the incident to the U.S. government in order to take
measure against the occurrence of similar incidents in future.
</P>
<P>
Both incidents are apparently related to NATO's ongoing
airstrikes on Yugoslavia that started on March 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Dialog on Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- China urged the United States
to hold dialogs rather than resorting to confrontation on human
rights.
</P>
<P>
"The only way is to have dialogs rather that resorting to
measures of confrontation, because facts or history have already
proved that confrontation will get nowhere," said Li Zhaoxing,
Chinese Ambassador to the United States, in an interview by C-SPAN
here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"If we sit together and discuss patiently, and on the basis of
equality and mutual respect, we can reduce and eradicate some of
our differences," he said, "and that's good for all sides."
</P>
<P>
"But if you go to confrontation, it will not get anywhere. It
will cause damage not only to others but also to yourselves, " he
added.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said the UN Conferences on Human Rights in
Geneva in the past have indicated that to resort to confrontation
will always lead to failure.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the 90s, the United States has supported
anti-China resolutions at the Geneva human rights conferences for
seven years in succession, but each time it failed.
</P>
<P>
The Unites States announced that it will table an anti-China
bill in the 55th UN Conference on Human Rights, which was strongly
opposed by China.
</P>
<P>
"We demand that the U.S. side reverse its erroneous decision
immediately, and abandon its practice of interfering in China's
internal affairs," said Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun
Yuxi in Beijing Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhaoxing said that in general, China and U.S. have a lot in
common with regard to human rights, and the common grounds could
be expanded.
</P>
<P>
"But we also have differences, then we can sit down and
discuss," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that this is a post-Cold-War period, "so we
should do well not to let the cold-war mentality" hamper the
understanding and friendship between and among peoples of the
world.
</P>
<P>
"We should work together to make the world more prosperous and
beautiful," Li said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls Again After Close Above 10,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average fell again in the second day after closing above 10,000
as traders continued to get worried about the company earnings
and take profits.
</P>
<P>
The Dow finished down 127.10 at 9,786.16, retreating from an
88.80 gain in the first hour of trading. The index lost 220.62
points in the past two days after it crossed the five digit
milestone, finishing at 10,006.78 for the first time Monday.
</P>
<P>
The further retreat of the Dow index today was pushed by the
sign of distressed corporate profits. The Commerce Department
said in a report that for all of 1998, corporate profits slipped
2.2 percent, the first drop since 1989, when profits fell 4.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
The market was also affected after a jury in Oregon ordered
Philip Morris to pay 81 million U.S. dollars to the family of a
man who died of lung cancer after smoking Marlboros for four
decades.
</P>
<P>
Investors also adjusted their holdings to lock in earnings
ahead of the long weekend, driving the market down.
</P>
<P>
 Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index fell 14.38 at 1,286.37 and the technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index fell 18.53 at 2,461.76.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index was down 5.06 at 603.59 and the American
Stock Exchange composite index was down 1.33 at 710.30. The
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.15 to 397.63.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-6 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,422 up, 1,661 down and 488
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 922.06 million shares from 725.53
million in the previous session.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
