<HEADLINE> Nigeria Launches Nigeria '99 Stamps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Postal Service
Wednesday launched the commemorative stamps for the 10th World
Youth Soccer Championship tagged Nigeria '99 which is scheduled to
start on April 3 in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
At the launching ceremony, Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalami Abubakar warned in a message that "the government
would not tolerate failure on the part of those responsible for
Nigeria '99."
</P>
<P>
He challenged members of the local organizing committee and
managers of sports in the West African country to brace up to
ensure the success of the championship.
</P>
<P>
General Abubakar noted that the championship coincided with the
country's return to the mainstream of international politics after
years of isolation over human rights and democratization.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian media has recently been replete with complaints
from officials of the Federation of International Football
Association (FIFA) and football teams who began arriving in the
country at the weekend about the state of facilities in the eight
centers for the 21-day championship.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, FIFA withdrew the hosting rights from Nigeria over
fears about medical facilities in the most populous African
country.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed "charity stamps" specifically produced for sales during
the championship, the postal stamps will come in six different
denominations.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the stamps is football, Head of Media Relations of
the Nigeria Postal Service Jaiye Olaniyi explained, adding that
each of the stamps will carry a surcharge of 5 nairas (about 0.056
U.S. dollars) which is meant to be turned to the local organizing
committee of Nigeria '99 after sales.
</P>
<P>
He said that his establishment's other products and services
include sales of stamps, aerogram services comprising inland and
overseas postage, and philatelic services.
</P>
<P>
Video documentaries on Nigerian cultural heritage in postage
stamps would be played in the official hotels for Nigeria '99 as a
form of entertainment to visitors, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Postal Service has also planned to release for sale some
specialized postcards which are football related topics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
