<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FINA Tightens Rules Against Doping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- FINA, the world swimming
governing body, will tighten rules against doping, Mustapha
Larfaoui of Algeria, president of FINA, announced in an
extraordinary congress of FINA here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
FINA decided that swimmers from any federation will face out-of-
competition tests and the federation will be deprived of its entry
to any FINA swimming tournament for two years if four doping cases
are found in a period of 12 months.
</P>
<P>
Officials from FINA also said swimmers at the world short-
course championships in Hong Kong from April 1 to 4 would be asked
for the first time to give blood samples voluntarily to a group
studying ways to detect illegal use of growth hormones to improve
performance.
</P>
<P>
Urine samples are still normally carried out at the world short-
course championships.
</P>
<P>
FINA listed 2,187 doping tests in 1998, 22 of which turned out
to be positive. Half of the 22 doping cases were the ones
conducted by national federations.
</P>
<P>
FINA conducted 802 out-of-competition tests last year, and
national federations conducted another 1,185, it said.
</P>
<P>
In 345 tests so far in 1999, no positive cases have been
reported, FINA executive director Cornel Marculescu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990401.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Expresses Concern Over Russian Ship Deployments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Wednesday it was concerned at Russian plans to send up to seven
Navy ships to the Mediterranean to be close to the Kosovo
conflict.
</P>
<P>
"We are obviously concerned by the signal such a large
deployment might be sent to Belgrade and other countries in the
region," State Department spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Russia had told Turkey that seven ships from the
Black Sea fleet would transit the Bosphorus in two groups in early
April.
</P>
<P>
He said: "While the Russian Foreign Ministry has made it quite
clear that Russia does not intend to become entangled in the
conflict in the Balkans... the deployment of these ships we don't
see as a particularly helpful gesture."
</P>
<P>
Moscow's move came as Russian leaders unleashed another barrage
of criticism of NATO air strikes on Yugoslavia after Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov came home empty-handed from a peace
mission to Belgrade, officials here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
